<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HereComesBloomie's     09-23 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Here Comes Bloomie's,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bloomingdale's Comes to Chicago, Shaking Up Retail Game</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marshall Field's is the homegrown favorite in
this city's retail game. Now an invader from New York will sell its
wares on Michigan Avenue, raising a question for people with power
in their pocketbooks.
   ``Gosh, dahling, what's a shopper to do?''
   Bloomingdale's _ Big Apple boss, Gotham giant, 59th Street
strongman _ is opening Saturday a six-floor home a few blocks from
Lake Michigan, and there is gleeful speculation around town about
which retailer will have the registers ringing.
   ``For a while there will be blood in the streets,'' says Bill
Zwecker, a society columnist who monitors the pulse of Chicago's
upper crust for the Skyline weekly newspaper.
   ``Most people recognize this is a Bloomingdale's-Field's
battle,'' he said. ``It's been building up to a crescendo. There
has been an electricity to this arrival that I have never seen.''
   And when it comes to keeping customers happy, a little partying
can't hurt.
   Field's threw a benefit for the Lyric Opera of Chicago on Sept.
9 that was attended by 1,200 people. The gathering also celebrated
the $10 million renovation at Field's Water Tower store _ just a
brisk stroll from the new kid on the block.
   Partygoers clinked glasses with designers Bill Blass, Louis
Dell'Olio and Carolina Herrera as Field's brought out the heavy
artillery to woo the local elite.
   Bloomingdale's opening fete is Friday, and 2,500 people have
been invited to its benefit for the Chicago Symphony Orchestra.
   Invited guests will hear soothing strings, big band sounds and
contemporary rock on all six floors of the store. They will eat
Petrossian smoked salmon and sip fine wines and French champagne.
   The lineup of French couturiers attending will be headed by Karl
Lagerfeld.
   ``There will be plenty of people who will try to crash,''
Zwecker said. ``The people-watching will be unequaled.''
   That's fine with ``Bloomie's,'' as the retailer is
affectionately known in New York and eight other states. Chairman
Marvin Traub wants to make a big splash in the Windy City.
   The store's design was influenced by another local favorite,
Frank Lloyd Wright, the Oak Park architect whose Prairie Style
peppers Chicago and the suburbs. Five floors match various Wright
designs, including the Robie House, the Arizona Biltmore and
Tokyo's Imperial Hotel.
   When doors open to shoppers Saturday, the store will feature
guest appearances by some of the top names in fashion: Isaac
Mizrahi, Patricia Pastor and Paloma Picasso.
   General Manager Brian McMahon says Bloomingdale's will be
staffed by people who will earn only commissions on sales _ no
salary _ a first for the 17-store chain and a policy believed to
improve customer service.
   ``You name the store in the city of Chicago, we've ben able to
get the best people and bring them in,'' he said of recruiting a
sales team. ``It's only going to be a coup if we exercise the
service well.
   ``This market has created more interest in a store opening than
any I've ever been connected with, and I've lived in Washington,
New York and Boston,'' McMahon said.
   ``It's certainly uplifting, but I've tried to tell everybody to
retain a high level of humility. There's nothing worse than
building up a crescendo, believing your own press and then having a
shopper come in and say, `This isn't what I expected.'''
   At Marshall Field's, reaction to Bloomingdale's opening is
low-key.
   ``Our game plan is to compete effectively against all
competitors, and Bloomingdale's is one them,'' said Gary Witkin,
executive vice president.
   ``I think our attitude about business is no different today than
it was a year ago.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
