<DOCNO> AP880923-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Deaver Bjt   09-23 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deaver, Bjt,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Urges Imprisonment For Deaver In Perjury Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Sentencing set for 9:30 a.m. EDT; will be topped</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecutor in lobbyist Michael K. Deaver's
perjury trial says the former presidential aide should be
imprisoned for lying under oath about his ``cynical exploitation''
of his White House connections.
   Independent counsel Whitney North Seymour Jr. told U.S. District
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson that a prison term ``will have a
deterrent effect on the ethics and conduct of political insiders.''
   ``A sentence of incarceration will warn them that being caught
lying under oath about their activities will result in their going
to prison,'' Seymour said in a memo submitted for today's
sentencing.
   Deaver, 50, former deputy White House chief of staff, was
convicted last December of lying to the House Energy and Commerce
oversight and investigations subcommittee and a federal grand jury
impaneled at his request to consider allegations that his lobbying
violated federal conflict-of-interest laws.
   Deaver faced a possible five-year prison term and a $6,800 fine
for each of the three convictions.
   His lawyers were expected to argue at today's hearing that their
client should receive a lenient sentence because of his successful
battle with alcoholism.
   A jury found Deaver guilty of lying when he told the grand jury
he couldn't recall contacting Reagan administration officials on
behalf of major corporations that paid him six-figure fees to
represent their interests in Washington.
   A longtime friend of President Reagan and his wife, Nancy,
Deaver also was convicted of lying by denying he helped South
Korean trade envoy Kim Kihwan get a brief Oval Office appointment
to hand Reagan a personal letter from President Chun Doo-hwan.
   Seymour said evidence at the trial about Deaver's lobbying
``revealed a pattern of cynical exploitation of the governmental
process as a vehicle for private gain.''
   ``If the president's friend can get away with perjury, then the
field is wide open for every one in the privileged class to do the
same,'' the prosecutor said.
   Seymour has recommended eliminating what he called loopholes in
federal ethics laws that prevented him from prosecuting Deaver for
substantive conflict-of-interest violations.
   The prosecutor said Deaver's activities were typical of
```government consultants' ... who potentially threaten the
integrity of government by back door access to public agencies.''
   During the trial, prosecutors presented evidence that Deaver
contacted a number of high government officials, including
Secretary of State George Shultz and then-Secretary of
Transportation Elizabeth Dole, on behalf of major corporations that
paid his firm six-figure retainer fees.
   Last week, Seymour dismissed defense contentions that Deaver's
memory was clouded by alcoholism, arguing that he showed
``extraordinary recall'' about many events about which he was
questioned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
