<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Wright-CIA     09-23 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wright-CIA,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Speaker Keeps Up Criticism Of CIA Role In Nicaragua</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Ethics committee to meet in closed session at 10 a.m. EDT;
top prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright is continuing to
criticize CIA efforts to promote unrest in Nicaragua and seeking to
focus attention on what he calls misguided Reagan administration
policies, while Republicans upbraid him for revealing government
secrets.
   The House ethics committee was meeting today to consider an
official complaint against Wright, D-Texas, that questioned whether
the speaker violated House rules prohibiting disclosure of
classified information when he first disclosed the covert CIA
operation on Tuesday.
   Ethics committee chairman Julian Dixon, D-Calif., said the panel
would have to act on the complaint by House GOP Leader Robert
Michel of Illinois, and Republican Conference chairman Dick Cheney
of Wyoming. But he said the issue would be treated separately from
an existing ethics probe of Wright on unrelated matters.
   The matter was likely to be complicated by the sensitive nature
of the information involved. Michel said if an investigation were
launched, ethics committee staff members would have to gain
top-secret security clearance to be permitted access to any
relevant information.
   Speaking to reporters Thursday, Wright denied that he had broken
any rules or revealed classified information. His disclosure that
the CIA has instigated demonstrations in Nicaragua aimed at
provoking the leftist government could have been gleaned from
information available publicly, he contended.
   ``I didn't say anything that was revealed to me as classified
information,'' Wright said.
   But Wright was vague when asked how he learned of the covert
operation, instead seeking to focus attention on what he called the
error of the policy itself.
   ``In late August of last year I became aware that elements of
the U.S. government were seeking to disturb the domestic
tranquility in Central America, to foment disturbances with a view
to seeing if they could provoke'' the Sandinistas into a crackdown
that would derail peace talks, Wright said.
   ``That seems to me just intolerably two-faced,'' he said. Wright
added that he had been given ``indirect assurance'' that the
practice has now been halted.
   Wright attributed the move to investigate him to White House
pressure on Michel, but added: ``They lose on this one, because we
are on the side of democracy.''
   Regardless of the outcome, the new investigation of Wright only
added to an already long list of woes for the speaker. The ethics
panel, formally known as the Commitee on Standards of Official
Conduct, already is investigating Wright on unrelated allegations
of financial misconduct.
   A House panel on Thursday voted to give the committee an
additional $550,000 to pursue that investigation, which Dixon said
could continue into next year, depending on what is unearthed.
   ``It's taking a lot of time,'' said Rep. John T. Myers, R-Ind.,
the senior minority member of the ethics committee. ``It takes a
lot more in-depth investigation than we ever anticipated.''
   The latest controversy prompted harsh criticism of Wright by
Republican members of Congress, including a primary Senate sponsor
of legislation to tighten Congress' control over covert CIA
activities.
   The senator, William Cohen of Maine, said the speaker's comments
had apparently violated non-disclosure rules and jeopardized the
bill.
   ``The clear implication ... is that the speaker's statement
could only have been derived from classified information in the
possession of the House Intelligence Committee,'' Cohen said. ``The
speaker owes his colleagues in Congress and the American people an
explanation.''
   Cohen, the vice chairman of the Senate Intelligence Committee,
said the disclosure also could doom opposition members who are
jailed for anti-government protests to longer prison terms or ``a
harsher fate,'' and would give the Sandinistas an enormous
propaganda boost.
   And Rep. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, called the action
``inexcusable.''
   ``This government simply cannot function if each individual
member (of Congress) takes it upon him or herself to decide what
can be declassified,'' she said.
   House Majority Leader Thomas Foley, D-Wash., said the
legislation to require notice to Congress of covert actions within
48 hours, which had been due to come before the House next week,
might be put off until the following week because of the press of
other legislation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
