<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ShuttleExperiment     09-23 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle Experiment,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Tries Again with Space Shuttle Experiment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Shuttle-Space Coast, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A medical student who thought his dream of
sending a science project into space exploded with the ill-fated
Challenger mission will get another chance with the launch of the
space shuttle Discovery next Thursday.
   ``It's good to continue something you believe in,'' said Richard
Cavoli, whose work was praised by President Reagan in his 1986
State of the Union Address.
   Cavoli, now a second-year medical student at the University of
Buffalo, said he feared that the Challenger disaster would put an
end to manned space exploration.
   ``I was afraid people would say it wasn't worthwhile,'' he said
Thursday at a news conference in Buffalo. ``I think it is. A lot of
problems we have on earth can be solved in space.''
   Cavoli's project involves growing crystals under zero-gravity
conditions. He theorizes that gravity creates currents in chemical
solutions that disrupt formation of crystals. He said lead-iodide
crystals formed in space might be larger and purer and lead to
improved film for X-rays and improved semiconductors in computers.
   Cavoli, 24, first thought of the experiment as a high school
student. While he attended Union College in Schenectady, school
officials sponsored the experiment, spending more than $14,000.
   Union chemistry Professor Charles Scaife helped Cavoli refine
the experiment and rebuild the equipment destroyed in the explosion.
   The project is one of only two student experiments being
conducted by Discovery astronauts. Other experiments that were part
of the Challenger mission have been cancelled by NASA.
   Cavoli was in Washington watching a broadcast of the Challenger
launch when the space shuttle blew up, killing the seven astronauts
aboard. President Reagan had planned to single him out as a ``young
American hero'' in his annual state of the Union address,
originally scheduled for that evening.
   Just after the disaster, Cavoli was in the Oval Office with the
president and three others scheduled to be saluted in the address.
   ``He was just like the rest of us, in shock,'' Cavoli said. ``He
was very somber in the beginning, but then he tried to pick things
up a bit for the sake of the rest of us.''
   Cavoli returned a week later to be recognized when the speech
was rescheduled. He sat with first lady Nancy Reagan and stood as
Congress applauded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
