<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0622EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DrugBill-Provisions TwoTakes 550-1 09-23 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Bill-Provisions, Two Takes, 550-1,100</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Drug Bill Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The major anti-drug initiative passed by the
House by a 375-30 vote Thursday covers every possible method of
fighting illegal narcotics. Listed by major categories, the bill
would:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>LAW ENFORCEMENT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Give the Justice Department six months to present Congress with
a system that would allow gun dealers to identify felons attempting
to purchase handguns.
   _Revoke probation for any probationer found in possession of a
firearm.
   _Allow the death penalty for anyone who intentionally kills a
person during a drug felony. If capital punishment is not imposed,
the penalty must be a minimum of 20 years and a maximum of life
imprisonment.
   _Permit introduction of evidence, in federal criminal cases,
that was obtained in an unconstitutional search provided that
officers acted in the ``good faith belief'' they were acting
lawfully.
   _Establish civil penalties of up to $10,000 per violation for
possession of small ``personal use'' amounts of marijuana, cocaine
or any other illegal drug. The government could obtain a conviction
by proving ``clear and convincing evidence,'' far easier than the
``beyond a reasonable doubt'' standard in criminal cases. The
provision includes appeal rights.
   _Require a minimum five-year prison term for conviction for
possession of ``crack,'' a potent drug mixture with a cocaine base.
   _Impose tight controls over chemicals used to produce cocaine,
heroin and other dangerous drugs. Manufacturers, distributors,
importers and exporters would keep records on transactions and
report them to the attorney general. Imports and exports could be
suspended to prevent diversion for clandestine drug manufacturing.
   _Renew assistance to state and local governments for drug
enforcement through 1992. States would be required to pass through
federal money automatically to localities eligible for awards of
$25,000 or more. State and local contributions for matching funds
would rise from $1 for every $3 of federal money to a 50-50 split.
   _Increase money for enforcement by the Drug Enforcement
Administration, organized crime task forces, the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, the FBI and the prison system.
   _Raise penalties for operating a locomotive, truck or other
common carrier under the influence of drugs or alcohol in cases
where death or serious injury results.
   _Authorize more money for the Coast Guard to increase its
personnel, and to operate, maintain and purchase anti-drug vessels,
aircraft, radar and other equipment.
   _Increase money to the Customs Service for additional personnel,
enhancement of the air interdiction program, and to buy an X-ray
imagery, vapor sensitive cargo scanning device.
   _Prohibit the distribution of anabolic steroids without a
prescription.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TREATMENT, TESTING AND REHABILITATION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Establish a new block grant program for the states, designed to
reduce transmission of acquired immune deficiency syndrome by
intravenous drug abusers. States could use the money to develop and
operate treatment programs; train counselors; test individuals for
the AIDS virus; and construct or renovate facilities for treatment
of drug abusers. Money would be provided through 1991.
   _Authorize money to states for programs to prevent alcohol and
drug abuse, and treatment and rehabilitation services. Money
provided through 1991.
   _Require government regulations for certification of
laboratories performing toxicological urinalysis for drug testing
programs.
   _Require that if any money under the bill is used for AIDS
counseling and testing, the tests must be conducted confidentially,
with informed consent, and with pre- and post-test counseling.
   _Allow the secretary of the Health and Human Services Department
to make grants to expand capacity of drug treatment programs.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880923-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0623EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DrugBill-Provisions 1stadd   09-23 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Bill-Provisions, 1st add,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHN: treatment programs.
^ADMINISTRATIVE ACTIONS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Require that many federal benefits be denied for five years
from those convicted of two or more drug-related offenses within a
10-year period; and denial for 10 years for those convicted of drug
distribution. Included would be public housing, licenses, contracts
and student loans, and veterans' assistance in cases of
distribution convictions. Excepted would be retirement, welfare,
health and disability assistance.
   _Provide grants to states for enforcement of anti-drug programs
that take away a convicted drug offender's right to drive.
Suspension would have to last six months for a first conviction and
at least one year for repeat convictions within a five-year period.
   _Provide grants to states to help implement drunken driving
enforcement programs, provided the programs include immediate
suspension of licenses of those found driving under the influence
of alcohol.
   _Allow the Federal Aviation Administration to modify aircraft
registration and pilot certificate programs to ensure positive,
verifiable and timely identification of aircraft owners and pilots.
   _Establish an Office of Drug Enforcement Coordination under the
president to establish policies, objectives and priorities for
federal drug enforcement.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BANKING</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Prohibit financial institutions from issuing checks or money
orders of more than $3,000, unless recipients have an account with
the institution or can show verifiable forms of identification.
   _Allow the treasury secretary to monitor domestic financial
institutions in any specified geographic area where drug
trafficking and money laundering are prevalent.
   _Permit federal or state law enforcement agencies access to
financial records of any bank official, controlling shareholder, or
customer whenever there is reason to believe such records are
relevant to possible criminal activity. Exempts the current
requirement to notify the bank's insiders of the activity.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>EDUCATION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Authorize money through 1991 for drug abuse education and
prevention programs for youth gangs.
   _Allow the secretary of education to finance innovative alcohol
abuse education programs targeted at young children, especially
children of alcoholics.
   _Authorize money through 1991 to establish a year-round National
Youth Sports Program for disadvantaged youth, replacing a current
summer-only program. Special emphasis to be given to drug abuse
education and prevention.
   _Authorize grants to states through 1991 for drug abuse
education-prevention programs for youths in the juvenile justice
system.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FOREIGN POLICY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Permit a $10 million U.S. contribution toward a Latin American
regional anti-narcotics force if a hemispheric presidential
conference approves such an entity.
   _Require the secretary of state to revoke passports of convicted
drug violators, if international boundaries were crossed in
committing the offense.
   _Provide $5 million in rewards for information on terrorists in
the drug trade.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>GOVERNMENT CONTRACTORS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Set a condition that recipients of federal grants or contracts
maintain drug-free workplaces. Recipients must agree to follow
stringent requirements, including a published policy prohibiting
the unlawful manufacture, distribution, possession or use of a
controlled substance; and have drug-free awareness programs.
   _Require contract employees convicted of a drug offense to
notify their companies, who in turn must inform the government. The
employer must take appropriate action against the worker, or
require participation in an approved drug abuse assistance or
rehabilitation program.
   _Permit the government to remove a grant or contract if a
recipient files a false certification of a drug-free workplace,
fails to carry out certification requirements, or employs a number
of workers convicted of drug violations occurring in the workplace.
</TEXT>
