<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TextileBill     09-23 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Textile Bill,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Set to Act on Textile Import Bill Amid New Veto Threats</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tightened restrictions on textile, apparel and
shoe imports appear set for final House approval, but President
Reagan is expected to veto the measure.
   ``The textile and apparel industry probably has the least
persuasive case for further import restriction of any major
industry in this country,'' seven Cabinet officials said Thursday
night in a letter to lawmakers.
   The House was set to vote today on the measure, which would
freeze this year's imports of textiles and apparel at 1987 levels
and limit future growth to 1 percent a year. Non-rubber footwear
imports would be capped indefinitely at 1987 levels.
   The measure _ designed mainly to shield domestic producers from
foreign competition _ also would establish a pilot program under
which the government would auction import licenses.
   To build support from the farm lobby, the measure includes a
guarantee that any country increasing its purchases of U.S.
agricultural products would get a break on textile and apparel
quotas. Korea and other Asian textile-producing nations are among
the largest purchasers of American grain and other farm goods.
   The House passed a version of the bill a year ago. It was voting
today on a move to accept four Senate changes: the import license
auctions, the farm-goods provision, a change in the base year for
the freeze from 1986 to 1987 and special restrictions on shipments
of foreign-made silk neckties.
   Supporters of the textile, apparel and shoe industries say the
bill is needed to protect American jobs that otherwise will be lost
as imported textiles flood the U.S. market. They point to heavy
layoffs amid a surge in foreign-made goods that that entered the
country in the early 1980s.
   The Reagan administration counters that the textile industry is
flourishing and that the layoffs came about largely because the
manufacturers adopted automated production methods to become more
competitive in the face of stepped up competition.
   ``If this bill is passed, we and the president's other senior
advisors will recommend that he veto it,'' said a letter to
lawmakers Thursday from U.S. Trade Representative Clayton K.
Yeutter and six other Cabinet officers.
   They said the measure ``would be extremely harmful to our
country. It would hurt U.S. consumers. It would provoke retaliation
against U.S. exports, violate our international obligations and
undermine our efforts to obtain a more open trading system for U.S.
exports.''
   The veto threat was viewed as unlikely to budge supporters, and
the administration was expecting the bill on Reagan's desk within
days.
   ``He wouldn't veto it until next week,'' White House spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater told reporters earlier Thursday.
   Reagan vetoed a similar bill in 1985 and an override attempt
that was deferred seven months to move it closer to congressional
elections failed to gain the two-thirds support needed.
   Rep. Ed Jenkins, D-Ga., occupant of the ``textile seat'' on the
House Ways and Means Committee, said last week he hoped Reagan
would relent and sign. But if the president could not be budged, he
said, he wanted to force Reagan to use his veto pen one more time
rather than killing it through inaction with a ``pocket veto''
after Congress adjourns.
   On the eve of the House vote, Rep. Butler Derrick, D-S.C., said
there were ``a number of people who have told us they aren't going
to vote with us tomorrow but have agreed to vote for an override.''
   He said he believed that textile forces were ``about 14 short''
of the two-thirds support needed for a veto override. He said,
however, that the override attempt would not be mounted in the
House before the first week in October and thus ``we have 10 days
to work on that.''
</TEXT>
