<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0635EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AirRoute     09-23 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Air Route,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Continental Gets Coveted Seattle-Tokyo Route</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Continental Airlines has been awarded the
highly contested and lucrative air route between Seattle and Tokyo
after two years of controversy, a court challenge and questions
about possible conflict of interest.
   United Airlines, which currently flies the route, said it would
ask the Transportation Department to reconsider its decision, which
came Thursday. American Airlines also had been in the running to
win the route on a permanent basis.
   The decision by the Transporation Department came after the
Justice Department refused to challenge a federal court decision
which in August ordered the route given to Continental, according
to a high-ranking Transportation Department official.
   The official, who asked not to be identified, said
Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley had argued strongly to appeal
the case, but that Justice spurned the idea.
   ``He (Burnley) believes we could have had the (court) opinion
reversed on appeal,'' the official said.
   The department made no formal announcement of its order.
   Opponents of the ruling have 10 days to petition the department
to reconsider its decision, said DOT spokesman Bob Marks. He said
the provision for a reconsideration request is standard in such
cases.
   In Chicago, United issued a statement saying it was encouraged
that the ruling allowed for a reconsideration request, adding that
the company ``strongly believes that the merits of the case clearly
support United's retention of the route.''
   A department administrative law judge had recommended
Continental for the route originally, but a succession of senior
department officials disagreed, chosing at one point United and
then American.
   Before a final decision could be made, a federal appeals court
ruled in late August that the original administrative law judge's
recommendation should stand. Continental had filed suit because it
had not been given the route.
   The Seattle-Tokyo route previously had been flown by Pan
American World Airways, but United assumed the route temporarily
when it purchased Pan Am's Pacific Division in 1986.
   The Transportation Department approved United's acquisition of
the Pan Am routes only under the condition that the Seattle-Tokyo
route be dealt with separately.
   Last year a DOT administrative law judge recommended that the
route be given to Continental, but that recommendation was subject
to review by a senior department official designated to deal with
international air routes.
   The official, Vance Fort, then deputy assistant secretary for
policy and international affairs, disagreed and recommended United.
   Later, however, a conflict of interst problem arose because Fort
at the time had been negotiating for employment at Flying Tiger
Airlines, which stood to benefit depending on which airline got the
Seattle-Tokyo route.
   Although no action was taken against Fort, the case was returned
to another administrative law judge, who also recommended that
United keep the route. But that decision was overruled by Fort's
successor, who recommended American.
   The department was about to make a final decision, presumably
American, when the federal court ruling on Continental's suit
intervened.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880923-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0320EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDSTesting Bjt   09-23 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Testing, Bjt,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Defeats Mandatory AIDS Testing for Prisoners, Marriage
Applicants</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top prospects uncertain</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill to expand voluntary AIDS testing among
high-risk individuals neared House passage with wide bipartisan
majorities turning back proposals to force tests on prisoners,
hospital patients and marriage license applicants.
   Lawmakers also defeated by a large margin a proposal requiring
states to collect identifying information on people who test
positive for the AIDS virus.
   Opponents successfully argued that anonymous testing is a much
better way to attract people at highest risk of being infected with
AIDS and that testing resources need to be concentrated on those
people rather than populations that probably haven't been exposed.
   ``Let's not take limited resources ... and waste them,'' said
Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., chief sponsor of the testing measure.
``Let the states do their own efforts as they see fit.''
   The Waxman bill would give states complying with its terms an
extra $400 million a year to conduct widespread, voluntary AIDS
testing and counseling.
   It also would protect the confidentiality of counseling and
testing records, speed up research into acquired immune deficiency
syndrome and create a national commission to advise Congress on
issues raised by the fatal disease.
   Final House action could come as early as today. The bill then
goes to the Senate.
   The Human Rights Campaign Fund, a political action committee for
the gay and lesbian community, praised the House for rejecting what
it called hostile amendments proposed by Rep. William Dannemeyer,
R-Calif., and other conservatives.
   ``Members of the House have sent a clear signal to Rep.
Dannemeyer and others who support irrational, punitive AIDS actions
that the time has come for responsible AIDS policy,'' the fund's
executive director, Vic Basile, said in a statement.
   The virus that causes AIDS, a fatal disease, most often is
spread through close contact with contaminated blood products or
semen. Its principal victims have been homosexuals and intravenous
drug users.
   The House agreed to require testing of prisoners convicted of
prostitution or crimes related to sexual assault or IV drug abuse.
The plan was approved 266-137 as an alternative to mandatory
testing of all prisoners.
   Amendments defeated Thursday included:
   _A proposal to require testing of all marriage license
applicants in states where the incidence of AIDS infection is over
one in 1,000, sponsored by Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla. It lost
304-91.
   Rep. Edward Madigan, R-Ill., said his state's program has
identified nine applicants infected with AIDS out of 75,000 people
tested, at a cost to newlyweds of $400,000 for each identified
case. He said the governor has requested it be repealed.
   Rep. Lindy Boggs, D-La., said her state repealed its requirement
after a year because it was an economic hardship, produced a
significant number of false positive tests and did nothing for
those groups at highest risk. ``Let's not force our mistake on the
rest of the nation,'' she said.
   _A proposal to require hospitals in high-incidence states to
test virtually all inpatients between ages 15 and 50, sponsored by
Dannemeyer. It lost 302-89. Health workers are expected to treat
all patients as infected and protect themselves accordingly,
Madigan said.
   _A proposal to require reporting of AIDS-infected individuals
with enough information to locate them, another Dannemeyer
initiative. It lost 327-70.
   Proponents accused Congress of ignoring the need for information
on the epidemic. But opponents said demographic data on
AIDS-infected people must be reported under the bill and
identifying information would drive people underground.
   The lawmakers cited the case of Oregon, where a switch to
anonymous testing resulted in a 125 percent increase in the number
of homosexual men being tested and a 56 percent increase in the
number of prostitutes tested. They also noted that in South
Carolina, a switch to name reporting resulted in a 51 percent drop
in the number of homosexual men being tested at a Charleston site.
</TEXT>
