<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Debate-Strategy Bjt   09-23 0823</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Debate-Strategy, Bjt,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Setting Low Expectations Part of Campaigns' Debate Strategy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To hear Michael Dukakis' aides describe it,
George Bush is a world-class debater who gobbled up his Republican
opponents every time he sat down with them during the 1988 primary
campaign.
   But the Bush campaign begs to differ. ``Facts are facts.
Dukakis' strongest suit is debate format,'' says the vice
president's campaign manager, Lee Atwater, recalling the Democrat's
experience as host of a television discussion program in the 1970s.
   This is not a sudden outbreak of pleasantries on the rough and
tumble campaign trail to the White House. Instead, it's part of a
grand strategy leading to Sunday's kickoff debate of the fall
campaign, with each side trying to inflate the other candidate to
the status of political giant so their own man can come out looking
like a giant killer.
   That's not the end of it, either, as Bush and Dukakis point
toward Sunday's 90-minute set-to in Winston-Salem, N.C., the first
of two presidential debates this fall.
   Both men must ``try to win not so much the debate itself as the
news coverage of the debate'' afterward, says Larry McCarthy, a
Republican political consultant not involved with Bush's campaign.
   That means carefully scripted, highly quotable utterances that
make the candidate look strong and convey his message and will be
rebroadcast time after time after time in the network news coverage
that follows the debate.
   And it means a smile isn't just a smile.
   ``Even the reactions will probably be staged'' while the other
candidate is talking, in case the gestures are being recorded by
another camera, he said.
   The psychological warfare isn't confined to manipulating the
public expectations of the two men.
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if they have a big batch of Bush
supporters outside the hall so all he (Dukakis) sees when he enters
the hall are Bush signs,'' McCarthy said.
   Many Republicans and Democrats say Dukakis probably has more to
gain in the debate and Bush has more to lose. That's because the
vice president has held the momentum in recent weeks and the trends
in the polls have been his way.
   Dukakis' advisers say the most important thing for him is to
appear presidential _ an elusive, ill-defined quality _ if he is to
succeed, while Republicans say Bush must avoid a major gaffe that
would reverse the gains he has made in recent weeks.
   ``The public has got to look at this man and think he's
presidential,'' says Francis O'Brien, a Dukakis adviser. ``It's a
cumulative thing. You sit there and you look at what he says and
how he looks. If you can cross that threshhold, that's an enormous
leg up for a candidate for president.''
   Watch Dukakis' behavior, says Republican consultant Eddie Mahe.
If he is constantly on the attack, it is a sign that he, too,
believes the Republicans are headed for victory unless he can
succeed in rattling Bush. If he is less aggressive, it probably
means he believes the race has settled back down and he has time to
make his points, Mahe added.
   Mahe, who is not involved in preparing the vice president for
the debate, says ``all George Bush has to do is as he did in
earlier debates and be a natural and reassured and deliberate
individual.''
   He recommends Bush begin his answers with a positive statement
about his own views and then wind up with a critical comment about
Dukakis.
   Bush successfully deflected potentially embarrassing questions
dealing with the Iran-Contra affair and taxes during the primary
debates, and Mahe says he can and should be able to anticipate
anything Dukakis throws at him.
   ``You have to avoid being strident. I would try to have thought
through every possible line of attack, and they are calculable _
Noriega, offshore oil drilling.''
   Leslie Dach, Dukakis' communications adviser, says this isn't a
make or break event. ``It isn't like 1984 when if the Democratic
candidate didn't knock the other guy's lights out he was history,''
he said.
   ``Michael Dukakis will be tough and he'll be engaged but we
don't have a haymaker strategy.''
   Atwater agrees that the debate isn't ``the end of the world one
way or another.'' He adds, ``As long as the candidates are
discussing the issues, it's to George Bush's favor.''
   Peter Hart, a Democratic pollster, says that for Bush, ``the big
thing is to be able to be consistent and to be able to say
something that goes beyond being peripheral and negative'' and
establish himself as an independent political force apart from
President Reagan.
   McCarthy, who worked for Sen. Bob Dole during the Republican
primaries, said Bush needs to ``come off as having more of a
positive message than we've seen from him recently.''
   Dukakis ``has to be relaxed and warm and have a couple of good
funny lines'' at Bush's expense, he said.
</TEXT>
