<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DentalHealth 1stLd-Writethru a0711 09-23 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dental Health, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0711,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Many U.S. Kids Decay-Free; Other Problems Still Unconquered</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to reflect that tooth decay goal was
reached in previous survey; picks up 7th graf pvs, ``We have...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As many as two-thirds of the nation's children
are free from tooth decay, but other dental health problems remain
unsolved, federal health researchers said Thursday.
   Preliminary results from a 1986-87 survey of U.S. schoolchildren
show more than 65 percent of the nation's 9-year-old children free
of tooth decay, the national Centers for Disease Control reported.
In a 1979-80 survey the figure was 49 percent.
   ``The downward trend in dental caries (tooth decay) in U.S.
schoolchildren has been occurring over the past two decades. The
decline has occurred in all age groups and all regions of the
country,'' the CDC said in its weekly report.
   But, the CDC said, tooth decay remains a persistent problem for
some high-risk groups, including poor children and minority
children.
   And while federal health officials' goal of no tooth decay in 40
percent of the nation's 9-year-old children has been surpassed,
three of 11 other dental-health goals for 1990 are unlikely to be
reached, the CDC said. One other objective has been reached,
progress is being made toward four, and information is not
sufficient to assess the other three, the Atlanta-based agency said.
   ``We have indications that the dental health of children has
improved, and we're very encouraged by that,'' said Dr. Susan
Szpunar, a CDC dental health specialist. ``But it's something we
have to look at with cautious optimism; there are still a lot of
dental health problems in the population which need to be taken
care of.''
   The trend in dental health in the United States, which the CDC
termed ``positive and encouraging,'' could be an omen to a new
problem, she said.
   ``The problem right now is people saying that if their kids
aren't getting cavities, they don't have to go to the dentist,''
she said. ``Another problem is communities that fluoridate (water
supplies) saying `Should we keep fluoridating?'
   ``That's a real dangerous question. The reason for the
improvement is the kids are getting it (fluoride). If it stops,
we'll probably see a reverse.''
   In addition to reducing tooth decay in children, the nation has,
according to the CDC, achieved one other dental health goal for
1990: making three-quarters of U.S. adults aware of the need for
good personal oral hygiene and regular professional care to control
periodontal disease.
   Three of the 12 goals are not likely to be met by 1990, the CDC
said: having no schools or health-care facilities offering
cavity-causing foods; having all school athletes wear recommended
mouth guards; and having 95 percent of the people with community
water getting fluoridation.
   The CDC noted that removing sugar from schools would mean an end
to band candy sales _ ``and that's difficult to tell people to
do,'' Ms. Szpunar said. Only three college sports require mouth
guards _ football, hockey and men's lacrosse _ and only 62 percent
of the population on community water get fluoride.
   Progress has been made toward four other goals, the CDC said:
reducing gingivitis _ gum inflammation _ and destructive
periodontal disease in adults to around 20 percent; making 95
percent of schoolchildren and parents aware of the risk factors for
dental disease and the benefits of fluoride; having a system in
place to monitor U.S. dental health; and having systems in place to
monitor public-health preventive measures.
   The CDC said insufficient information is available to assess
progress in three other areas: gingivitis in children, getting
fluoride to children who aren't on community water systems and
improving children's personal dental hygiene.
</TEXT>
