<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0454EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Nicaragua     09-23 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Nicaragua,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Denies It Blocked Visas For Nicaraguans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department has denied charges it
blocked visas for Nicaraguan officials planning to attend next
week's opening of the U.N. General Assembly, but Nicaraguan
President Danield Ortega has cancelled his trip.
   ``We have not denied the Nicaraguans visas,'' department
spokesman Charles Redman said Thursday. ``We're processing their
visas. The Nicaraguans applied late.''
   Redman said U.S. officials normally require 15 working days for
processing Nicaraguan visa applications but that the Sandinista
officials made the request on Sept. 13 for a Sept. 24 arrival in
New York. The assembly gets under way on Sept. 26.
   Of 60 visas requested, 30 have been expedited, including those
of Ortega and his family and senior foreign ministry officials,
Redman said.
   Other officials said the State Department is planning to approve
the remaining visa requests on Oct. 4, 15 working days after the
applications were submitted. By that date, Ortega had planned to be
back in Nicaragua.
   ``This arbitrary and illegal attitude constitutes a denial of
Nicaraguan rights,'' Nicaraguan Deputy Foreign Minister Victor Hugo
Tinoco said in Managua as he announced that Ortega was canceling
his trip that was to have included a speech to the General Assembly.
   Rudi Boone, a State Department spokesman, said late Thursday he
had no comment on Ortega's decision.
   Asked whether the department could expedite the visas in time
for Ortega and his entourage to attend the General Assembly, Boone
said, ``I could not say.''
   Nicaragua's ambassador to the United Nations, Alejandro Serrano
Caldera, accused the State Department Wednesday night of blocking
the visa requests.
   On Thursday, Leonor Huper, acting head of the Nicaraguan Embassy
in Washington, reiterated the charge and she denied Redman's
assertion that Ortega's family members had received visas.
   She also disputed Redman's statement that the visa applications
were not filed in time.
   ``We requested the visas with enough time,'' she said.
   Marcos Wheelock, minister counselor of Nicaragua's Organization
of American States delegation, said Ortega had planned to fly from
New York to Washington on Sept. 29 to address the OAS permanent
council.
   Wheelock said OAS rules require that the United States, as host
country, permit each member state to staff its delegation as it
sees fit.
   Thus, the U.S. decision to delay approval of some visa requests
until after Ortega's scheduled OAS speech ``interferes severely''
with Nicaragua's rights as an OAS member, Wheelock said. He added
that Nicaragua has lodged a protest with OAS Secretary General Joao
Baena Soares.
</TEXT>
