<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     09-23 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Readying For Debate After Responding To Bush Visit With
Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis set aside today to cram for his
debate showdown with George Bush after responding to the Republican
nominee's visit to Boston with a pointed attack labeling him
``AWOL'' in the nation's war on crime and drugs.
   The Democratic presidential nominee was spending the entire day
with his staff and advisers preparing for Sunday's debate. His only
scheduled public appearance was an early morning game of catch with
Boston Red Sox center fielder Ellis Burks outside Dukakis' home.
   In town to help Dukakis prepare is New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley,
and the Democratic nominee planned to take part in a mock debate
after morning briefings.
   Dukakis spent part of Thursday preparing for the debate but he
was forced to alter his schedule to defend his record on crime from
attacks by Bush, who popped into Boston to pick up a police union
endorsement.
   ``His administration has waged not a war on crime but a war
against crime control programs,'' Dukakis told a rowdy afternoon
rally outside his Statehouse office.
   ``We're here to give George Bush what Joe Friday used to ask
for: the facts ma'am, just the facts,'' Dukakis told the crowd of
law enforcement officials and supporters before criticizing Bush
and the Reagan administration for cutting aid to local police and
for allowing drug imports into the United States to soar.
   The law enforcement officials, representing 100,000 officers in
eight states, were quickly summoned to Massachusetts in a Dukakis
effort to blunt the impact of the Bush endorsement by leaders of
the 1,500-member Boston police union.
   One of them, representing the largest police organization in
Bush's adopted home state of Texas, prepared the crowd for Dukakis
with a fiery attack on Bush.
   ``I'm the only damn Texan in ton today representing police
officers,'' said Ron DeLord of the Combined Law Enforcement
Associations of Texas, which represents 8,000 officers across
Texas. DeLord said Bush failed in his assignment to curb drug
trafficking across the Texas border.
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, in town to help with debate
preparation, also pitched in at the Dukakis counterattack.
   ``I'm tired of this pandering,'' Cuomo said of the Bush
campaign. ``I'm tired of the simplistics and the distortions by
people like the vice president.''
   For his part, Dukakis delivered an emotional rhetorical flogging
of the vice president that delighted his partisan audience and
seemed to invigorate Dukakis.
   ``We're here today to investigate a felony _ assault and battery
on the truth,'' Dukakis said. ``What George Bush is doing to the
truth in this campaign is a crime.''
   For weeks, Dukakis aides have been fuming at what they see as
Bush's misrepresentation of Dukakis' record on crime and the
environment and of the Massachusetts economy.
   Dukakis stepped into the fray Thursday, saying Bush came to
Boston two weeks ago to ``impersonate an environmentalist'' and was
back again to ``impersonate a law enforcement officer.'' The
Massachusetts governor also said Bush has ``mugged the truth''
every time he has spoken about the state's economy.
   Dukakis noted that crime in Massachusetts has dropped 13.7
percent in the past five years while the federal rate has risen,
and he touted Masschusetts' ranking as the industrial state with
the lowest homicide rate.
   Dukakis also addressed an issue at the heart of Bush's effort to
portray the Democrat as soft on crime _ a Massachusetts furlough
program that until amended earlier this year allowed passes to
first-degree murderers.
   Dukakis said the federal government last year granted furloughs
to nearly 16,000 inmates, including ``hundreds and hundreds of drug
pushers and drug traffickers.''
   One reason leaders of the police union said they endorsed Bush
was because Dukakis did not attend the funerals of three Boston
officers recently killed in the line of duty. Dukakis, in an
apparent challenge to the argument, said the suspect in one of the
slayings had been paroled from a federal prison after serving less
than half of his 15-year term for bank robbery.
</TEXT>
