<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Quayle-Pollsters     09-23 0702</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle-Pollsters,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle a Negative So Far for Republicans, Pollsters Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leading pollsters say the choice of Dan Quayle
as a running mate has done more harm than good for Republican
George Bush, but they're far from predicting it will cost Bush the
presidential election.
   Those poll takers who point to the preference among voters for
Sen. Lloyd Bentsen as a possible successor to the presidency point
out that the vice presidential running mate doesn't normally decide
the outcome of an election. They also point to some negative
feelings toward Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis.
   ``I believe Quayle could be Bush's Achilles heel,'' CBS News
pollster Warren Mitofsky said Thursday at a panel discussion
sponsored by the National Council on Public Polls.
   Mitofsky said his surveys show that on the question of who is
preferred for vice president, Bentsen or Quayle, the Democrat is
preferred by a two-to-one margin.
   Mitofsky said that among the group of voters paying the most
attention to the campaign, Dukakis held a slight lead. But he said
when this group was asked who they would favor if no running mates
were involved, Bush led.
   ``They'll vote for Bush over Dukakis if that's all they have to
do, but if you put Quayle in the mix, they go the other way,'' he
said. ``It's only a small move, but it's there.''
   Gordon Black, who polls for CNN and USA Today, said Quayle has a
2-to-3 percentage point overall negative effect for Bush in his
polls.
   His survey shows 23 percent saying they are less likely to vote
for Bush because of Quayle, while 6 percent said they were more
likely to vote for Bush because of his running mate.
   But Black said that appeared to be offset by an unrelated
finding that the ``liberal'' tag Bush has pinned to Dukakis has
caused 30 percent of respondents to say they are less likely to
vote for the Democrat. Nine percent said liberalism made them more
likely to support Dukakis.
   Richard Wirthlin, who is conducting surveys for the White House
and the Republican National Committee, did not not release his poll
findings on the Indiana senator, but he said in an interview later
that they were in line with Mitofsky's.
   ``On the net, it has been more negative than positive,'' said
Wirthlin.
   ``The question is to what extent do people vote for the ticket
because of the vice president,'' he said. ``In the past, that has
not been a big issue.
   ``Personally I think two things: One, before this campaign is
over Quayle is going to look better than he does right now. Two, 99
percent of Americans are going to vote for either Bush or Dukakis
and not for Quayle or Bentsen.''
   Quayle's negatives appeared most recently in an NBC News-Wall
Street Journal poll released Thursday. More voters viewed him
unfavorably than favorably, 37 percent to 33 percent, a reversal
from his 40-22 favorable rating last month. Half the voters said
Quayle was a bad choice.
   A Gallup poll for the Times Mirror Corp. also referred to Quayle
as ``the Achilles heel of the Republicans.'' While Quayle did not
appear to be an issue on which votes were swinging directly, poll
analyst Norman Ornstein said Quayle would be ``more of an issue
that the overall numbers suggest'' because of questions over Bush's
judgment.
   Peter Hart, a frequent pollster for Democratic candidates, said
negative reaction to Quayle has increased over the past month _
apparently as doubts about his qualifications were considered more
fully by Americans.
   Bush maintains a small lead over Dukakis in most recent national
polls. Hart said that should Dukakis win, however, Quayle would be
cited as the major reason.
   ``You look a month later, and it's much worse for Dan Quayle,''
said Hart, who is polling for the Chicago Tribune. ``The perception
over the last month has gone steadily more negative, and the
perception persists that he's just really not ready to be either
vice president or president.''
   Wirthlin said Quayle has a chance to ease negative perceptions
about him in his debate with Bentsen on Oct. 5, and he predicted
Quayle will look better by Election Day.
</TEXT>
