<1ST_LINE>r p PM-NBC-JournalPoll     09-23 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NBC-Journal Poll,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC-Journal Poll: Bush 45, Dukakis 41</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Presidential Nominee George Bush lost
support among Democrats who voted for President Reagan in 1984, but
more voters are viewing Democrat Michael Dukakis as too liberal, a
new poll says.
   The NBC News-Wall Street Journal poll Thursday showed Bush
leading Dukakis 45-41.
   Bush's running mate, Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana, also lost
ground. More voters viewed him unfavorably than favorably, 37
percent to 33 percent, a reversal from his 40 percent to 22 percent
favorable rating last month. Half the voters said Quayle was a bad
choice.
   Twenty-five percent of the Reagan Democrats in the poll
supported Bush, down from 35 percent a month ago. The Democrats are
making a special effort, especially in the campaigning by Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen of Texas, to win back those more conservative
Democrats.
   The survey of 2,360 likely voters in the poll had a margin of
error of two points, meaning that Bush and Dukakis were essentially
tied. Other recent polls have had similar results.
   A poll late last month after the Republican National Convention
put Bush ahead by 47 percent to 40 percent among likely voters.
   The newest poll, done Sept. 16 through Monday, found Bush
continuing to do better with men than with women, and losing ground
with women since last month.
   Although he lost ground with Reagan Democrats, Bush gained with
his criticism of Dukakis as liberal. A third of the voters polled
said Dukakis was too liberal to be a good president, up from 27
percent last month. The 54 percent who disagreed was down from 64
percent.
   Bush was rated as a good vice president by 54 percent and
Dukakis as a good governor by 52 percent. But the voters by 62-25
percent said being vice president was better training for the
presidency than being a governor.
   Bush led substantially among men, 50-38, but the support of
women flipped from 44-40 with Bush ahead last month to Dukakis
ahead by the same margin now.
   The overall result of 45 percent to 41 percent produced a margin
similar to those in an Atlanta Constitution poll done last week,
which put the race at 43-40, and a Washington Post-ABC News poll,
which put it at 50-46.
</TEXT>
