<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka-Violence     09-23 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka-Violence,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minister Says 231 Killed By Militants In One Month, Emergency
Extended</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior official disclosed that at
least 231 people had been killed in rebel attacks by both Tamils
and Sinhalese in one month.
   Public Administration Minister Montague Jayawickreme said
Thursday the killings took place during between Aug. 16 and Sept.
15.
   Jayawickreme was speaking during a Parliament debate over
extending emergency rule in the island nation. After his speech,
the government again extended emergency rule for a month.
   Emergency rule gives the country's security forces wide-ranging
powers of arrest and detention. It has been extended monthly since
May 1983, when the Tamil insurgency began in the northern and
eastern provinces of Sri Lanka.
   Tamil militants, who claim they are discriminated against by the
island's Sinhalese majority, have waged a war for an independent
Tamil nation in the north and east, where they are a majority.
   More than 8,500 people have been killed in the war.
   Jayawickreme said the Sinhalese militants were responsible for
150 of the 231 slayings in the past month. Tamil insurgents had
killed 81 people, he said.
   Jayawickreme said that of the 150 people killed by the Sinhalese
People's Liberation Front, 51 were in public officials and 99
others were police informants and relatives of supporters of the
ruling United National Party.
   Of the 81 people killed by Tamil insurgents, 62 were civilians
and 19 were Lankan security personnel, he said.
   The People's Liberation Front has vowed to kill supporters of an
India-mediated peace accord signed in July 1987. The accord was
aimed at giving a greater measure of autonomy to Tamils.
   The Sinhalese extremists claim too many concessions were given
to Tamils, who are mostly Hindus and make up 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people.
   The Sinhalese form 75 percent of the island's population and
control its government and military.
   More than 450 people, including military and civilian supporters
of the government, have been victims of the Sinhalese group's
campaign since the accord was signed.
</TEXT>
