<1ST_LINE>u i PM-OlympicProtests     09-23 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Olympic Protests,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Use Tear Gas To Break Up Olympic Protest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students staged an
anti-Olympics rally and attacked riot police with firebombs and
rocks today. Troopers fired tear gas to drive the protesters back.
   About 500 students, shouting ``Oppose dictatorial Olympics!''
attempted to march out of Korea University in eastern Seoul and
were blocked by hundreds of riot police in green combat fatigues
and black-visored helmets.
   Students hurled firebombs and rocks at the police, who used tear
gas and hurled back rocks during the half-hour clash.
   It appeared to be the first time riot police had used tear gas
in Seoul since the Olympics began Saturday. The government banned
tear gas in an effort to limit limit anti-government protests.
   No one was reported arrested or injured in the clash, which was
confined to the main gate in front of the school, about 15 miles
from the main Olympic venues.
   Radicals have staged a number of protests against the Olympics,
but they have been small and largely peaceful. Most Koreans are
critical of the protests and want the Games, which end Oct. 2, to
be a success.
   During the earlier campus rally, student leaders denounced the
South Korean government for not sharing the Olympics with communist
North Korea. They also claimed the government would use the Games
to cement authoritarian rule.
   Speakers said the Games were being used by the Seoul government
to perpetuate the division of the Korean Peninsula. The Games, they
said, should be shared to help reunite the two Koreas.
   Protesters also demanded the release of a student leader
arrested by police Thusday for organzing anti-government protests
in recent months.
   North Korea is boycotting the Olympics because its demand to be
a co-host was rejected by the International Olympic Committee,
which said the Olympics are awarded to a single city and cannot be
shared.
   The Korean Peninsula was divided at the end of World War II and
separate republics were founded in the north and south in 1948.
</TEXT>
