<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua-US 1stLd-Writethru a0455 09-23 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-US, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0455,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Cancel Trip To U.S., Blame Reagan Administration</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to ADD details of U.S. denial and quote,
picks up 10th graf pvs `American citizens...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega canceled plans
to speak before the United Nations next week because of charges the
United States illegally put off issuing visas to members of his
delegation.
   U.S. officials said the problem arose because the Nicaraguans
submitted their request late.
   Speaking Thursday night when he announced cancellation of
Ortega's trip, Deputy Foreign Minister Victor Tinoco said at a news
conference, ``This arbitrary and illegal attitude constitutes a
denial of Nicaragua's rights.''
   Alejandro Bendana, secretary-general of the Foreign Ministry,
said in a telephone interview that the Reagan administration
deliberately was setting up obstacles to stop the Sandinista
government from speaking at the United Nations and the Organization
of American States.
   ``Evidently the Reagan administration is petrified that we may
sound reasonable,'' he said.
   The cancellation of the trip came two days after House Speaker
Jim Wright revealed a covert CIA operation to destabilize the
leftist government.
   It also comes two months after Nicaragua expelled U.S.
Ambassador Richard Melton and seven other diplomats, accusing them
of destabilizing the country. The United States retaliated by
expelling eight Nicaraguan diplomats from Washington.
   The U.S. Embassy notified the Nicaraguan Foreign Ministry on
Thursday that only half of the 60 visa requests for visits to the
United Nations and the Organization of American States in
Washington had been processed.
   It said the other visas _ for Cabinet ministers, high-level
foreign ministry officials and journalists _ would not be ready by
Saturday, when President Ortega and his delegation planned to leave
for the United States. Ortega planned to speak before the U.N.
General Assembly Wednesday in New York and Thursday before the
Organization of American States in Washington.
   ``We have not denied the Nicaraguans visas,'' State Department
spokesman Charles Redman said Thursday. ``We're processing their
visas. The Nicaraguans applied late.''
   Redman said U.S. officials normally require 15 working days for
processing Nicaraguan visa applications but that the Sandinista
officials made the request on Sept. 13 for a Sept. 24 arrival in
New York.
   But a high-level Nicaraguan Foreign Ministry official said the
15 working days applied only to visas for official state visits
between the two nations, such as those given to diplomats.
   American citizens who are not government employees do not need
visas to enter Nicaragua.
   Diplomatic relations between Nicaragua and the United States
have been strained for more than seven years. The Reagan
administration has supported Nicaraguan rebels since 1981 in their
war to oust the Sandinistas.
   Washington claims the Nicaraguan government threatens U.S.
national security by being a beachhead for communism. The
Sandinistas came to power in a 1979 revolutionary war that deposed
President Anastasio Somoza.
   The United States, saying the Sandinistas backed Marxist
guerrillas fighting in El Salvador, cut off economic aid to
Nicaragua in 1981 and imposed a trade embargo in 1985.
   On Tuesday, Wright, D-Texas, disclosed that the CIA had
instigated demonstrations aimed at provoking the Sandinista
government to take repressive actions.
   The Sandinistas in early July charged that the U.S. Embassy was
behind a plot to create internal disturbances. On July 11, the
Nicaraguan government expelled Melton and the seven diplomats,
accusing them of backing an anti-government demonstration a day
earlier.
   Washington dismissed the Sandinista claims and expelled
Nicaraguan Ambassador Carlos Tunnerman and seven of his colleagues.
   Wright's statements about the CIA attempting to foment internal
problems appeared to confirm earlier Sandinista claims.
   Managua has yet to make an official statement about Wright's
revelations. ``My impression is that it's no secret the Central
Intelligence Agency for the past eight years has been trying to
overthrow the government,'' Bendana said. ``The obvious can hardly
strike us as news.''
</TEXT>
