<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0348EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Salvador Bjt   09-23 0743</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador, Bjt,0766</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Villagers Mourn 10 Slain By Troops</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto SAL2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This peasant hamlet today
mourned 10 villagers, a tenth of its population, slain by
government troops in what witnesses said appeared to be the largest
incidence of civilian killings in four years.
   The government, through the Armed Forces Press Office, said the
villagers were ``subversives'' who died fighting troops.
   But more than a dozen relatives and neighbors of the dead who
witnessed Wednesday's events told The Associated Press that the
seven men and three women were killed with grenades and rifle fire
after being detained in their homes or while carrying out their
daily tasks.
   Benedicto Reyes, a resident of the nearby village of Santa
Teresa, said about 100 soldiers marched past his house Tuesday
evening toward San Francisco, 30 miles east of San Salvador.
   At 5:30 the next morning, a squad appeared at the home of Jose
Atilio Rivas and his wife Maria Julia Argueta, according to Mrs.
Argueta.
   She said the soldiers thoroughly searched the home, then took
her husband away and ordered her to stay inside with the couple's
three young children.
   ``They said they were going to give him a talk,'' said Mrs.
Argueta. Her eyes red from weeping, she spoke only five feet from
where her husband's body lay in the village churchyard along with
the nine others.
   The 10 bodies, which villagers had carried in hammocks slung on
poles from the site of the killings a mile away, exhibited shrapnel
and gunshot wounds.
   Lucia Henriquez, 80, said she was watching her grandchildren
play in front of their adobe home Wednesday afternoon when soldiers
appeared and told her to take the children inside and remain there.
Her home is about 150 yards from the site of the killings.
   About the same time, according to several others detained in the
village schoolhouse, soldiers working from a list took four women
and one man from the school. One woman was released outside the
building, where more than half the villagers had been held most of
the day without food or water.
   According to the villagers, the other four were marched down a
rocky and muddy path to a ravine, where six others were being held.
   Mrs. Henriquez said she heard three loud blasts _ presumably
hand grenades _ and then sustained automatic rifle fire.
   The nearly 40 residents detained in the schoolhouse were
released Wednesday evening but prevented by the soldiers from going
down the path to the ravine. They found the bodies at dawn Thursday.
   A military press officer, asked Thursday about the villagers'
account, said the army had no further information but would
investigate the matter. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Relatives identified the victims as: Teresa Argueta, 47; Maria
Zoila Rivas, 45; Maria Jesus Sibrian, 27; Jose Maria Flores, Jose
Alfaro, Nicolas Alfaro, Francisco Alfaro, Ulises Sibrian, Jose
Atilio Rivas and Jesus Zepeda. The ages of the men were not known.
   Maria Gumercinda Melendez, 28, said she and her daughter Blanca
were walking to the nearby town of San Sebastian Wednesday when
they were detained by the troopers and held in the schoolhouse all
day.
   At mid-afternoon, the soldiers called the names of Ms. Argueta,
Ms. Rivas and Ms. Sibrian along with that of Francisco Alfaro and
Rosa Emilia Rivas, ahe said. The five stepped forward, were
blindfolded and led out.
   Ms. Rivas and others said troops accused the detainees of
supporting the Marxist-led Farabundo Marti National Liberation
Front which has fought El Salvador's U.S.-backed government for
nearly nine years.
   ``I don't feel safe here anymore,'' Ms. Rivas said. ``I would
like to leave, but I don't have anywhere to go.''
   Shortly before dusk some men began using picks and shovels to
open a large common grave in a nearby harvested cornfield. The
villagers buried seven of the dead there after dark.
   Relatives said the other three would be buried today.
   The last reported mass killing of civilians attributed to the
army took place Aug. 30, 1984 in the town of Las Vueltas in
Chalatenango province. Thirty-four people were killed there,
according to local and international human rights groups. No
officer or soldier was ever prosecuted.
   On Thursday, leftist guerrillas mounted one of their most
successful operations in recent months, killing at least 15
soldiers in an attack on an army post in the eastern Morazan
province, an army communique said.
</TEXT>
