<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Politics-Quotes     09-23 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Politics-Quotes,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quotes From the Presidential Campaign Trail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some comments Thursday from the
presidential campaign trail:
   
   GEORGE BUSH, receiving the endorsement of the Boston Police
Patrolman's Association in Michael Dukakis' backyard: ``Who was it
said that the police aren't there when you need them?''
   
   MICHAEL DUKAKIS, at a hastily planned but spirited
counter-rally, flanked by scores of police officers and elected
officials: ``We're here today to investigate a felony: assault and
battery on the truth. What George Bush is doing to the truth in
this campaign is a crime. We're here to give George Bush what Joe
Friday used to ask for: the facts, ma'am, just the facts.''
   
   CRAIG FULLER, Bush's chief of staff, saying the vice president
complained to a Panamanian official about drug-money laundering
during a visit five years ago, but did not discuss it with
Panamanian Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega: ``The notion that Vice
President Bush would sit down with the president of Panama and
discuss drug-money laundering should be a plus.''
   
   LLOYD BENTSEN, criticizing the GOP record on Social Security:
``Over the past eight years, George Bush and Dan Quayle and the
Republican party have waged unrelenting guerrilla warfare against
Social Security.''
   
   PRESIDENT REAGAN, accusing Dukakis and Bentsen of stealing
issues from Republicans: ``But it just doesn't sound right. They
use our words and borrow our tune, but the song is way out of key.''
   
   DAN QUAYLE, defending the Reagan-Bush administration policy of
bankrolling Contra rebels in Nicaragua: ``There is something in
this country that is called the Monroe Doctrine ... (that) says
foreign powers coming into our hemisphere ... is against the
national interest of this country. ... There is nothing wrong with
reminding the American people ... (and) Gorbachev that the Monroe
Doctrine is alive and well in America.''
</TEXT>
