<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0738EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CathedralAttack     09-23 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cathedral Attack,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>St. Patrick's Cathedral Will Keep Its Doors Open, Cardinal Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   St. Patrick's Cathedral will not change its
open-door policy despite the attack by a deranged, homeless man who
bludgeoned an elderly usher to death before being shot dead by
police, says Cardinal John O'Connor.
   The cardinal resanctified the historic midtown church Thursday,
referring to the rampage there Wednesday night as a ``special
sacrilege and tragedy.'' It was the first time in the church's
109-year history that the rite to cleanse and purify a profaned
sacred place was performed.
   O'Connor said the attacker, Jorge DelGado, 32, a Cuban
immigrant, was one of the many homeless people who seek refuge in
the church to avoid the elements or often just to find a place to
sleep.
   ``You can find them inside the church any time of the day,'' he
said, adding the Archdiocese of New York would not change its
open-door policy as a result of the incident. ``I would hate to see
us now get defensive.''
   O'Connor offered the morning Mass for the souls of both men:
DelGado, 32, a hulking ex-convict; and usher John Winters, 77, a
retired hospital guard from County Mayo, Ireland.
   Winters abandoned his retirement three years ago to work as an
usher at the landmark church on Fifth Avenue. ``He loved this
church and literally gave his life for it,'' the cardinal said.
   DelGado entered the country in May 1980 at Key West, Fla., a
political refugee using the name Jorge Cuellar Ayllon. Here he used
the names Cuellar and DelGado, received psychiatric care seven
times since 1983 _ most recently in April _ and had stayed
sporadically since 1986 at a men's shelter in Manhattan.
   In March, police took him to Roosevelt Hospital's psychiatric
ward after he created a disturbance at the cathedral. Police
requested he be held for evaluation, but the hospital released him,
the New York Post reported today.
   DelGado's date and place of arrival indicated he probably was
part of the Mariel boatlift, a wave of refugees from Cuba that
included released prison inmates and mental hospital patients.
   He had been arrested 11 times since April 1982, on charges
including robbery, weapons possession and assault. He pleaded
guilty to each charge and served a total of about 15 months in jail.
   DelGado frequented the cathedral in recent months, and in March
police removed him for being disruptive. He sometimes cursed
parishioners, once dashed a marble font to the floor and another
time pulled a crucifix from the wall, authorities said. But
Wednesday morning, 12 hours before his rampage, he took communion
before O'Connor and waited to receive the cardinal's blessing.
   That night, witnesses said, the 6-foot-4, 250-pound DelGado tore
off his clothes and ran into the cathedral, chanting under his
breath, carrying a pair of sneakers and some red carnations. He
beat a woman, clubbed Winters to death and struck and seriously
injured a police officer.
   Another officer killed him with a single shot.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
