<HEAD>Gunmen Break into House, Kill Catholic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen smashed their way into a
house in a Roman Catholic district of west Belfast today and killed
the owner as he came down the stairs to investigate the commotion,
police said.
   At least two gunmen took part in the pre-dawn attack, a police
spokesman said. They fled in a hijacked car that later was found
abandoned in a nearby Protestant enclave, he said.
   The killing bore the hallmarks of an attack by Protestant
militants, said the spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
No group immediately claimed responsibility.
   Police said the victim, who had been in bed with his wife, was
shot when he came down the stairs to investigate the break-in. The
couple's three children were asleep in other rooms, the spokesman
said.
   At least 70 people have been killed in political and sectarian
violence in the Protestant-dominated province this year.
