<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Korea-USFilm     09-23 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-US Film,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Korean Theaters Closed To Protest Independent Imports Of U.S.
Films</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major movie theaters in Seoul shut
down today to protest independent distribution of U.S. motion
pictures such as ``Fatal Attraction'' in South Korea.
   At least 32 cinema houses in Seoul took part in a one-day
strike, which came in retaliation for the distribution of ``Fatal
Attraction,'' the first U.S. film to be shown by distributors
dealing directly with American exporters.
   ``Oppose direct film distribution by U.S. exporters,'' read a
placard at one cinema.
   The new direct U.S. distribution of films to South Korean
cinemas, which bypasses local distribution companies, is part of
trade liberalization measures.
   ``Fatal Attraction'' is scheduled to be shown this weekend in 12
South Korean cinemas.
   Film directors, producers and distributors issued a statement
calling for the boycott of the film and withdrawal of U.S. movie
distribution offices. Opposition political parties and dissident
groups joined in with promises to support the boycott campaign.
   On Thursday, President Roh Tae-woo told the Cabinet that the
liberalization of South Korean markets would be inevitable to avoid
trade conflict with the United States, South Korea's biggest
trading partner. Roh called for freer but gradual imports of U.S.
films, agricultural and marine products.
</TEXT>
