<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Guatemala-USFast     09-23 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Guatemala-US Fast,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Americans End Embassy Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Americans protesting U.S. policy in
Central America ended their weeklong fast in front of the U.S.
Embassy by sharing tortillas and wine.
   The four, holding hands with Guatemalan supporters Thursday,
chanted, ``We all want peace and freedom in this world.'' They also
replaced protest banners affixed to the embassy gates with
Guatemalan flags.
   The protesters, who plan to return to the United States today,
are Dale Ashara-Davis, 34, of Baltimore; Sara Story, 26, and
Charlie Liteky, 57, both of Washington; and John Schuchardt, 49, of
New Haven, Conn.
   The protest began Sept. 14 when the Americans threw blood on the
embassy steps and chained themselves to the gates of the compound.
Authorities have not interfered with the protest.
   In Honduras, 16 Americans were arrested and deported after
similar demonstrations in front of the U.S. Embassy in Tegucigalpa,
the capital, and at the U.S. air base in Palmerola, 40 miles to the
northeast.
   The demonstrators, who belong to a group called Project
Independence, timed their protests to coincide with the Sept. 15
anniversary of Central America's independence from Spain in 1821.
   John Mateyko, a group spokesman in Washington, said last week
the protest was ``religious-based and non-violent'' against what
members view as ``the immoral and dangerous policy'' of the Reagan
administration in Central America.
   The U.S. government supports the government of El Salvador
against leftist insurgencies and has backed rebels in Nicaragua
fighting the leftist Sandinista government. It has supported
Guatemala against leftist rebels.
</TEXT>
