<DOCNO> AP880923-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0747EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BenefitIndictments     09-23 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Benefit Indictments,0639</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>10 Accused of Defrauding Employee Benefit Plans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health care executives in several states
and a promoter have been charged with offering kickbacks in return
for lucrative employee-benefit contracts with businesses and labor
unions.
   ``Workers around the country are adding another dollar or two''
to their health premiums because of secret kickbacks, said Richard
Held, chief of the FBI office here.
   The indictments against 10 people and one Maryland-based health
benefit company, which include charges of racketeering,
embezzlement and falsifying records, were unsealed Thursday in San
Francisco, Atlanta, Baltimore, Chicago and San Diego.
   Federal agents working undercover handled thousands of dollars
in kickbacks for securing health benefit contracts for companies
and labor unions during a three-year investigation, Justice
Department officials said.
   The kickbacks, collected by brokers and health plan
representatives, were in addition to commissions that legitimate
brokers charge for arranging contracts, the officials said.
   One of the indictments says an FBI agent was promised $7,500 a
month _ a rate of 75 cents for each employee at National
Semiconductor Inc. of Santa Clara, Calif. _ by brokers for securing
a health benefit contract. The money, which was never paid,
apparently would have been charged to the employer.
   Among those indicted were United HealthCare Inc. of Baltimore
and one of its executives, and the former benefit plan managers for
two Chicago-based labor unions.
   But the central figure in the case is Angelo Commito, 43, of
Fairfax, Calif., described as a middleman in the business of lining
up health benefit contracts for companies and unions. Authorities
said he was arrested Thursday in Palm Springs and released on $1
million bail.
   In the Atlanta indictments, Commito and five other people are
accused of conspiracy, mail fraud, wire fraud and money laundering
in a plan to defraud the Munford Corp., a retailing concern, and
its employee welfare plan in the selection of a second prepaid
optical program and an alcohol and drug abuse counseling program.
   The fraud allegedly involved using Commito's companies to pay
kickbacks to a government agent who posed as Munford's
representative for the purchase of the programs.
   Commito and another man also were accused of devising a scheme
to defraud the National Semiconductor Corp. of Santa Clara, Calif.,
of money the two allegedly agreed would be used to pay kickbacks to
a government undercover agent who posed as the company
representative. The kickbacks were to persuade the firm to buy an
alcohol and drug rehabilitation program.
   U.S. Attorney Joseph Russoniello of San Francisco called Commito
``a known associate of traditional organized crime individuals ...
members of the Aiuppa family of Chicago.''
   The charges against him include violating the Racketeer
Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act in schemes against four
benefit plans. The maximum sentence is 20 years in prison and a
$250,000 fine.
   At a news conference, Russoniello said certain types of health
benefits newly required by a number of states, such as drug and
alcohol rehabilitation, appeared to be particularly attractive
targets for corruption in the soliciting of benefit contracts.
   ``The amount of money that passes through this kind of program
has made it ripe for the plucking,'' the prosecutor said. ``It's
difficult to know how widespread, nationally, the abuse is.''
   He said the Justice Department would seek to consolidate all the
cases in San Francisco.
   Bill Slavin, president of United HealthCare, declared the firm
``innocent of all charges.'' Commito made no immediate comment on
the indictments.
   United, which provides prepaid optical, dental and medical
prescription services to more than a million families in 42 states,
is accused of taking part in the scheme to pay the government agent
who was soliciting an optical contract for employees of Munford.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
