<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0604EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-OilRigFire     09-23 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Rig Fire,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seach Resumes for Missing Man in Oil Platform Explosions, Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers aboard helicopters searched
for a missing British worker today and shipboard crews battled
flames from explosions and fire on a North Sea oil platform,
officials said.
   All the other 66 people on the semi-submersible platform Ocean
Odyssey escaped Thursday from the explosions and fire. Rescue
helicopters took them to this port city, and one was reported to
have suffered slight injuries.
   The rig is about 110 miles from where Occidental Petroleum's
semi-submersible oil rig Piper Alpha was swept by explosions and
fire on July 6, killing 167 people in the world's worst oil rig
disaster.
   Police identified the missing man in Thursday's accident as
25-year-old Timothy Williams, a radio operator. Rescuers resumed
their search for him at dawn today.
   Support ships today fought more flames as gas continued to well
up to the platform.
   The platform is owned by the New Orleans-based Ocean Drilling
and Exploration Co. and operated by the Atlantic Richfield Co. of
Los Angeles.
   William Waver, the owner's vice president, was quoted by the
London newspaper The Independent today as saying the two blasts and
fire apparently followed a buildup of gas pressure.
   Mud pumped into exploratory drilling pipes usually stops any
pocket of high pressure gas or oil from forcing its way to the
surface. So-called blow-outs occur when the pressure is too great
to be held back by the mud. Valves fitted to prevent blow-outs
sometimes fail.
   James Murphy, one of the 66 crewmen who escaped, told reporters
in Aberdeen that two explosions engulfed the platform in flames.
   Murphy, 42, an engineer on the platform, said crewmen had been
worried about the gas pressure for the past six weeks.
</TEXT>
