<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     09-23 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JASPER, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sidney Hicks thought he would never again
hear his blue-fronted Amazon parrot whistle the theme from the
``Andy Griffith Show.'' Then Arthur turned up in Texas.
   ``I`m just thrilled to death,'' said Hicks, who owns dozens of
parrots. ``I had just given up on it. I had reconciled myself to
the fact that I would never see him again.''
   The bird, valued at $1,000, was stolen in its cage July 1 from
the front porch of Hicks' home.
   The theft attracted widespread news coverage because of Arthur's
specialty _whistling the theme song from the ``Andy Griffith
Show,'' which featured George ``Goober'' Lindsey of Jasper.
   Police Sgt. Jeff Sparks said that 22-year-old Roger V. Hill,
arrested this week in an unrelated burglary, admitted taking the
parrot and giving it to relatives in Pasadena, Texas. An arrest
warrant charges Hill with first-degree theft in the parrot-napping.
   ``The people who had him didn't know anything about it being
stolen,'' Hicks said. ``They said he was whistling and talking and
in good shape.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WARREN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thomas Gossett calls it art, but city
officials objected that the nuts-and-bolts sculpture displayed in
front of his auto parts business was a bit too earthy.
   The stainless-steel sculpture is a seven-foot-tall ``male'' bolt
with arms and legs chasing a shorter, partially stooped ``female''
nut with her arms in the air.
   Officials in this Detroit suburb found in suggestive and
offensive, and forced Gossett to remove it from in front of his
Creative Metals Inc. business.
   ``It doesn't fall within the city's sign ordinance,'' said Mayor
Ronald Bonkowski. ``Our building department has received many calls
and letters about this, this object, for want of a better word. The
city suggested he remove it from in front of his business and he
did. We're happy about that.
   ``I've seen it, and it doesn't qualify as a sign. Is it art? Not
to me.''
   Gossett said he made the sculpture for a friend at least three
years ago but took it back when the friend received complaints for
displaying it.
   The sculpture stayed in Gossett's shop until a few weeks ago,
when he moved it out front to free some space. His attempts to
mollify complaints failed.
   ``I tried putting clothes on them. A skirt on the girl and a
shirt and pants for the guy,'' he said. ``Sunglasses for both of
them. The city said, `Nice try, but they've got to go.'''
   Back inside his shop, Gossett plans to separate the figures and
set them up playing volleyball or something equally inoffensive.
But he expresses a little disappointment with his critics.
   ``In the art world, take Picasso. I see something you don't
see,'' Gossett said. ``Every art object is different. People are
looking at this thing as a dirty porno thing. It's not.''
</TEXT>
