<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0736EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Shuttle-OldRing     09-23 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle-Old Ring,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Old Nozzle Rings Not Part Of Discovery Boosters, NASA Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Shuttle-Space Coast, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA has determined that the space
shuttle Discovery's boosters do not contain the old model of a
nozzle ring used inadvertently in the final test of the redesigned
booster.
   Engineers rechecked inventory paperwork and re-examined X-rays
before concluding that the twin rockets scheduled to help lift
Discovery into space Thursday contain the correct, improved nozzle
inlet rings, NASA spokesman Ed Medal said Thursday.
   He said early X-rays of Morton Thiokol's boosters were enhanced
by computer and confirmed that the boosters are ``in the right
configuration.''
   Even if the old-design rings had been found, it was unlikely it
would have delayed the launch because the old rings performed well
in previous shuttle flights and tests, said Medal, the space
agency's spokesman at the Marshall Space Flight Center in
Huntsville, Ala.
   Engineers discovered earlier this week during regular post-test
examination that the nozzle inlet ring installed in the Aug. 18
test booster contained the old design. Morton Thiokol said the old
ring performed satisfactorily.
   The rings are inside the nozzle assembly at the tail of the
126-foot-long shuttle booster. They are not the O-rings in the
booster segment joints that were blamed for the Jan. 28, 1986,
explosion of the shuttle Challenger.
   The nozzle inlet ring has been only slightly modified since
then, while the segment joints have been extensively redesigned.
</TEXT>
