<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Hirohito 1stLd-Writethru a0467 09-23 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hirohito, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0467,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crowds Throng Imperial Palace to Wish Well to Ailing Emperor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with more bleeding, new British
tabloid attacks on Hirohito. Language in graf 12, `The newspapers
...' may be offensive to some readers. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of well-wishers huddled under umbrellas
today at the Imperial Palace to pray in the rain for ailing Emperor
Hirohito, and thousands more signed get-well registries around
Japan.
   His condition remained stable, but he needed two more blood
transfusions after continued hemorrhaging, palace officials said
today. The 87-year-old emperor, the longest reigning monarch alive,
vomited blood Monday from intestinal hemorrhaging, and he has been
in bed ever since.
   Crown Prince Akihito, who took over imperial duties temporarily
on Thursday, today presided over a Palace ceremony attended by
Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita to mark the autumnal equinox, a
national holiday.
   About 500 people with umbrellas and cameras lined up in front of
the Palace gates today and waited to take up calligraphy brushes
and put their names in a registry wishing the emperor a speedy
recovery. Some chanted Buddhist prayers.
   Palace officials said 23,000 people signed registries placed in
12 locations around the country Thursday. Today, officials were
setting up outdoor tents with more lists in front of other
government offices.
   One elderly visitor to the Palace wore a uniform of the Japanese
Imperial Army from the era of the Russo-Japanese War of 1904-05.
The man said it wasn't his, but he could find no other to wear.
   ``I felt I had to wear some kind of military uniform to come
before the emperor,'' he said.
   Under the constitution written during the post-World War II
occupation by U.S. forces, the emperor, who has ruled since 1926,
is only a symbol of the state with no real power.
   While highly popular with many Japanese, he is opposed by a
minority that views him as a remnant of the militarism that
dominated before and during World War II.
   Kenji Maeda, an official of the Imperial Household Agency that
runs Palace affairs, told reporters Thursday that Hirohito ate two
ice cubes that day and watched his favorite television serial.
   In Britain, tabloid newspapers renewed their attacks on Hirohito
today after Japan protested their negative coverage.
   The newspapers have called Hirohito evil and said he deserves to
go to hell for his acts during World War II.
   ``We cannot forget that in the name of Emperor Hirohito, the
Japanese army and navy launched a criminal attack on British
possessions in the Far East for no other reason than greed,'' the
London Sun quoted its unidentified spokesman as saying.
   In a letter published by The Sun, Japan's ambassador to Britain,
Kazuo Chiba, expressed ``astonishment and aversion that The Sun
should have carried an article such as this, which is so full of
ill will and which slanders a sovereign.''
</TEXT>
