<HEAD>Dollar Steady, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was little changed in subdued European
trading early today as the market waited for the weekend meeting of
the seven leading industrialized democracies.
   Gold prices were higher in Europe, touching $400 an ounce in
Zurich.
   Dealers said they expected trading to remain calm because most
players would be unwilling to make aggressive moves before
Saturday's meeting in West Berlin of financial ministers from the
Group of Seven industrialized nations.
   Banks and financial markets in Japan were closed today for the
national Autumnal Equinox Day holiday. In London, the dollar was
quoted at 134.45 yen, unchanged from its closing rate in Tokyo
Thursday.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Thursday:
   _1.8773 West German marks, down from 1.8790
   _1.5857 Swiss francs, down from 1.5870
   _6.3855 French francs, down from 6.3955
   _2.1182 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1150
   _1,402.00 Italian lire, up from 1,401.50
   _$1.2197 Canadian, up from 1.2188
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.6675, unchanged
from Thursday's late rate.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $399.60 a troy ounce, up
from $397.75 bid late Thursday. At mid-morning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $399.30.
   In Zurich, the noon bid price was $400.00, up from $397.00 bid
late Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 70 cents to close at a bid
$401.72.
   Silver bullion was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.25 a
troy ounce, unchanged from Thursday's late bid price.
