<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Afghanistan-Ambassador     09-23 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan-Ambassador,0388</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Afghan Ambassador: Interim Government Unworkable Solution
^By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghanistan's ambassador to India said
today a U.N. envoy's proposal for an interim government in his
country was an unworkable solution.
   Ambassador Abdul Samad Azhar also repeated his government's
accusations that the United States and Pakistan were continuing to
supply arms to Afghan guerrillas fighting that country's
Soviet-backed government, which he called a violation of the April
14 Geneva Accord.
   The accord provided for the withdrawal of half of the Soviet
Union's more than 100,000 troops in Afghanistan by mid-August and
all of them by Feb. 15, 1989. U.N. observers and others say the
Soviets are complying with the pact.
   Diego Cordovez, the U.N. envoy who mediated the accord, has
proposed the creation of a broad-based interim government to
replace President Najib's government, which is dominated by the
People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan.
   ``The suggestion by Diego Cordovez _ it is against our
principle, (our) policy,'' Azhar told foreign and Indian reporters
at a news conference at the Afghan Embassy, just down the road from
the Soviet Embassy in New Delhi's diplomatic enclave.
   ``What are the assurances that such a government can remain in
power, because such a government will demolish the existing policy,
the existing defense, the existing security?'' Azhar asked. ``Then
what will be the power of such a transitional government in
Afghanistan? It has not any solid base.''
   When asked if his remarks meant that Cordovez's proposal was
unacceptable to the Afghan government, Azhar described his remarks
as a ``personal'' view. To date no Afghan official is believed to
have expressed a similar view.
   Cordovez, who has been working for a peaceful resolution of the
Afghan war since 1982, has proposed that a traditional tribal
council decide the country's future.
   He said he had compiled a list of 30 impartial, respected
Afghans who could help convene the council and possibly form an
interim government of peace and reconciliation.
   ``We believe a broad-based government should be proposed in
Afghanistan,'' Cordovez said Sept. 15. A former U.N.
secretary-general for political affairs, Cordovez is now foreign
minister of Ecuador but remains U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez
de Cuellar's special representative on Afghanistan.
   Soviet troops intervened in Afghanistan in December 1979.
</TEXT>
