<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     09-23 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Soak Michigan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms stretched from northeastern Illinois
to western New York state today after drenching Michigan with up to
4 inches of rain, triggering a flash flood watch.
   Showers and thunderstorms also extended from the Texas Panhandle
and extreme western Oklahoma to southwest Texas. A few showers
lingered over central New Mexico.
   Skies were mostly cloudy from the southern Rockies to the
mid-Mississippi Valley and western New England, and over the
Pacific Northwest. Clear skies prevailed in the rest of the nation.
   Thunderstorms in lower Michigan on Thursday dropped up to 4
inches of rain on Grand Rapids and doused Battle Creek with 2
inches in two hours that night. The flash flood watch for southern
Michigan remained in effect early today.
   Showers and thunderstorms also moved over southern Wisconsin and
northern Illinois on Thursday evening. Strong winds downed trees in
suburbs southwest of Chicago, while Madison, Wis., received 1.37
inches of rain, breaking the precipitation record for the date of 1
inch, set in 1959.
   Showers and thunderstorms in west Texas on Thursday evening
generated strong winds that snapped power lines and blew the
awnings off buildings in Plainview. Winds gusted to 65 mph in
Crosby and 58 mph in Lubbock.
   The high temperature for the nation Thursday, the first day of
fall, was 97 degrees in Fort Smith, Ark., Lakeland, Fla., and
Wichita, Kan. It was the first day without a 100-degree reading
since May 30.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
along a cold front from New England to the Ohio Valley and the
Oklahoma Panhandle, with showers most numerous over eastern New
York state and New England; and cloudy to partly cloudy skies over
the upper Great Lakes and the upper Mississippi Valley.
   High temperatures were forecast to be in the 60s along sections
of the Pacific Coast, Washington state, northern Idaho, northwest
Montana, parts of the central Rockies, northern sections of the
upper Great Lakes and the upper Mississippi Valley and most of
Maine; in the 80s in California's inland valleys, southern New
Arizona, New Mexico and western Texas, and from central Oklahoma to
Kentucky and the Atlantic Coast from New Jersey to North Carolina;
in the 90s in the eastern two-thirds of Texas, the lower
Misssissippi Valley, the Gulf Coast, the southern Atlantic Coast,
Florida and the desert Southwest; and in the 70s in the rest of the
nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 33
degrees at Butte, Mont., McCall, Idaho, and Yellowstone National
Park, Wyo., to 82 at Corpus Christi, Texas, and Tampa, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 71 fair; Boston 58 cloudy; Buffalo 62
thunderstorm; Charleston, S.C. 68 fair; Cincinnati 73 fair;
Cleveland 75 cloudy; Detroit 66 foggy; Miami 74 fair; New York 65
cloudy; Philadelphia 65 partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 69 fair;
Portland, Maine 48 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 36 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 79 fair; Denver 49
fair; Des Moines 58 fair; Indianapolis 76 partly cloudy; Kansas
City 61 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 50 fair; Nashville 76 fair; New
Orleans 77 foggy; St. Louis 81 partly cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 51 fair; Anchorage 38 cloudy; Las Vegas 63
fair; Los Angeles 63 fair; Phoenix 74 fair; Salt Lake City 50 fair;
San Diego 64 fair; San Francisco 51 fair; Seattle 50 partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 55 cloudy; Toronto 61 showery.
</TEXT>
