<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Salvador-Attack 1stLd-Writethru   09-23 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador-Attack, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0496,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Lift Transport Ban, Then Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to restore dropped time element. Pick up
3rd pvs, ``The raid...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels attacked an army
post with mortars and catapult-launched dynamite, killing at least
15 soldiers in what appeared one of the most successful guerrilla
operations in recent months.
   Eleven guerrillas were killed and 11 soldiers were wounded in
the attack Thursday in eastern Morazan province, according to a
communique issued by the Armed Forces Press Office.
   The raid on the army post began an hour after guerrillas lifted
a road traffic ban that had paralyzed most transportation
nationwide since Monday. In lifting the ban, the rebels called on
supporters to step up sabotage of vehicles that had ignored the
measure.
   Marxist-led rebels of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation
Front have fought the the U.S.-backed centrist government for
nearly nine years. About 65,000 people, mostly civilians, have been
killed.
   Lt. Salvador Gonzalez said the attack began at 1 a.m. with
rebels firing mortar rounds and charges of TNT into a
communications post on Avocado Hill, north of Corinto, 120 miles
northeast of San Salvador.
   Gonzalez, spokesman for the 3rd Army Brigade, said the rebels
used catapults, similar to those used in medieval times, to launch
explosives into the base defended by about 50 men. The guerrillas
then attacked with rifle fire, he said.
   Gonzalez spoke by telephone from San Miguel, headquarters for
military operations in the eastern third of this small Central
American country.
   The guerrillas also stepped up their sabotage of power
transmission lines in several of El Salvador's 14 provinces.
   The rebels' clandestine Radio Venceremos said the ban _ the
fifth this year _ was lifted at midnight Wednesday. Bus and truck
traffic returned to normal Thursday.
   At least three vehicles were burned during the ban, which
reduced bus and truck traffic in the capital by about 70 percent.
Traffic on provincial highways was almost completely halted.
   Some buses and trucks that operated since Monday covered their
license plates trying to avoid reprisals.
   The guerrillas blew up about 35 utility posts or high-tension
towers after the transport ban began, military sources said. Four
eastern provinces were without electricity early Thursday because
of overnight sabotage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
