<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HurricaneHelene 1stLd-Writethru a0474 09-23 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hurricane Helene, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0474,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hurricane Helene Strengthens, But Still No Threat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with winds increasing to 130 mph
from 120 and with 6 a.m. location of storm. Picks up 10th graf,
`Its slow ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westerly breezes and atmospheric pressure zones in
the Caribbean may ultimately direct the course of Hurricane Helene
as it brings its 130 mph winds westward from the mid-Atlantic,
forecasters say.
   But if the season's fourth hurricane continues to strengthen it
could brush aside any weather systems in its path.
   ``Once a system reaches a certain level _ like Hurricane Gilbert
_ they are relatively unaffected by the atmosphere and weather they
encounter. They are just strong enough move the whole weather
around them,'' said Randy Lascody, a meteorologist at the National
Hurricane Center.
   Lascody said it will be at least until the weekend before
forecasters will be able to accurately predict the course of
Helene, which formed early Wednesday at 75 mph and increased to 130
mph winds today.
   On Saturday, Helene may be close enough to allow a
reconnaissance flight from Puerto Rico, said Lascody.
   ``Then we'll have some hard data to make a judgment about the
hurricane,'' he said.
   ``Everyone is pretty gun-shy now after Gilbert,'' said Lascody.
``Helene is a pretty strong hurricane but it's still far from
everything. It wouldn't be getting all this attention so soon if it
wasn't right after Gilbert.''
   Gilbert slammed into the Caribbean, northern Mexico and the
Texas Gulf Coast last week, killing hundreds and inflicting
billions of dollars worth of damage.
   At 6 a.m. EDT today, the center of the 250-mile wide storm was
at latitude 14.3 north and longitude 45.4 west, or about 950 miles
east of the Caribbean island of Barbados. Helene was moving
west-northwest at 10 mph and was expected to continue that course
and speed through Saturday, with a gradual turn to the northwest
thereafter.
   Its slow progress may give it time to draw more strength from
warm Atlantic waters.
   But air currents from a low-pressure trough over the ocean may
draw Helene northward into the open Atlantic, away from the
Caribbean islands and North America, said forecaster Miles Lawrence.
   Ocean storms become hurricanes when sustained winds reach a
minimum 74 mph. The Atlantic hurricane season runs from June 1 to
Nov. 30.
   Two other hurricanes this season caused only minor damage in
Mexico and the U.S. Gulf Coast.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
