<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0707EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-IndGovernor     09-23 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ind Governor,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bayh, Mutz Locked In A Bitter, Expensive Battle In Indiana</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A campaign of deep pockets and tit-for-tat
attacks is being waged in Indiana, where the son of former U.S.
Sen. Birch E. Bayh is trying to break the Republicans' 20-year hold
on the governor's office.
   The race between Republican Lt. Gov. John M. Mutz and
32-year-old Secretary of State Evan Bayh is shaping up as the most
expensive in Indiana history, a campaign fought through
point-counterpoint TV commercials.
   Mutz, 52, in recent weeks has questioned Bayh's integrity,
charging the Democrat plays fast and loose with the facts about his
own record.
   Bayh this week claimed the Mutz campaign ``stooped to a new
low'' in Indiana politics by engaging in character assassination.
He contended the attacks are prompted by poll results that show him
leading by six to 10 points.
   ``It's not easy being behind,'' said Bayh. ``It's a very
pressure-filled situation. ... I think there's probably a good deal
of frustration and pressure'' in the Mutz campaign.
   Neither side has disclosed how much it has raised or spent, and
the latest finance reports are not due until early October, but
Mutz's campaign hopes to raise $3.5 million and the Bayh campaign
expects more than $2 million.
   That could eclipse the previous Indiana spending record set in
1980 when Bayh's father and Dan Quayle, the current GOP vice
presidential nominee, spent a total of almost $5 million as Quayle
upset the three-term incumbent.
   Bayh could become Indiana's youngest governor this century.
Robert Orr, who at 70 is the nation's second-oldest governor, is
barred from a third four-year term. Indiana's last Democratic
governor was Roger Branigin, elected in 1964.
   The GOP has made an issue of Bayh's age and inexperience _ two
years as secretary of state to Mutz's 21 in public service _ and
tried to counter his famous name, running a commercial with the
line ``Experience is earned, not inherited.''
   The elder Bayh has raised money behind the scenes and makes
occasional appearances in his son's place. Some of Evan Bayh's top
campaign aides worked for his father.
   Indiana's high court earlier this year rejected a GOP attempt to
have Bayh declared ineligible to run under the constitution's
five-year residency rule. Bayh returned to Indiana in 1984 after
working as a lawyer in Washington.
   Bayh, in TV commercials, claimed to have led a fight to return
the profits from the state motor vehicle license branch to the
people, refused a raise and cut his office budget by 10 percent.
   Mutz countered that it was Orr who pushed through legislation
transferring the license branch from political to state control,
that there never was a final bill in the Legislature offering Bayh
a raise, and that Bayh spent more money in his first year in office
than his GOP predecessor did in his last year.
   The Mutz counterattack on television ends with the line, ``It's
a question of integrity.''
   Bayh stood by his claims and charged that Mutz favored the old
license system, took a 50 percent raise in 1985 and presided over
threefold growth in his office budget.
   A last-minute advertising blitz helped Bayh defeat Republican
Robert O. Bowen, son of former governor and current Health and
Human Services Secretary Otis R. Bowen, for secretary of state two
years ago.
   ``If he thinks that he can continue to portray half-truths and
partial truths and innuendo as he did in '86 and is doing now in
his television commercials, we just will not let him get away with
that,'' said Mutz.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
