<1ST_LINE>u i PM-BRF--BlindMasseurs     09-23 0137</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Blind Masseurs,0143</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blind Masseurs Ask Government for Protection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blind masseurs rapped police with their
walking sticks as hundreds rallied today to demand government
action against their sighted colleagues.
   The 400 blind demonstrators, who were driven to the law-making
Legislative Yuan in Taipei by friends, tried to enter the building.
   But police blocked the blind protesters, and some hit the
officers with their walking sticks. Police pushed them away.
   The protesters dispersed when lawmakers pledged to review their
complaints.
   Kuo Kun-hsiung, leader of the demonstration, complained that
many massage parlors employ young girls as masseuses. He said the
practice violates a law that says only blind people can work in the
business to protect the welfare of the disabled.
   Several thousand of the estimated 10,000 blind people in Taiwan
work as masseurs.
</TEXT>
