<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Leaders-Glance 1stLd-Writethru   09-23 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Leaders-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0471,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lebanese Leaders At-A-Glance</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS profile of Hoss; SUBS 3rd graf pvs, `Raymond Edde ...'
to DELETE incorrect reference to Edde as president during French
mandate; pickup 4th graf pvs, `Suleiman Franjieh ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Lebanon, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are profiles of Gen. Michel Aoun, appointed prime minister
of Lebanon, the three leading presidential candidates, and Moslem
Premier Salim Hoss. Lebanon's unwritten covenant requires that the
president be a Maronite Catholic and the prime minister a Sunni
Moslem. Aoun is a Maronite, and Hoss is a Sunni Moslem.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   GEN. MICHEL AOUN _ Age 53, from southern Beirut suburb of Haret
Hreik. Mother was naturalized American. Youngest commander ever of
the 42,000-strong army. Was graduated from the Lebanese Military
Academy in 1958 as an artillery lieutenant. Speaks French, English,
Spanish, Italian, Arabic. Aoun commanded crack 8th Brigade trained
by U.S. Marines and it remains his main power base. Says he is a
non-partisan in Lebanon's turbulent politics. Has warned the army
will take control of the country if the politicians fail to elect a
president.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   RAYMOND EDDE _ Represents moderate line which advocates
Christian coexistence with other groups. Now 75 years old, was
member of Parliament representing the Byblos district north of
Beirut since 1953, except in 1964. Ran unsuccessful presidential
campaigns in 1958 and 1976. Held various Cabinet positions. Went
into exile in France in 1976 after three assassination attempts.
Opposes all foreign interference in Lebanon and says he will not
return from France, even if elected, unless Israel withdraws its
troops from southern Lebanon.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SULEIMAN FRANJIEH _ First elected parliamentary representative
of Zghorta, in north Lebanon, in 1960. Franjieh, now 78, retained
the post until elected president in August 1970. During first three
years in office, relied on the use of force to impose order and
demanded that the Palestinians stop launching operations against
Israel from Lebanon. Civil war broke out in 1975, one year before
his six-year term was due to expire. Personal friend of Syrian
President Hafez Assad since stay in Syria in 1950s. Accepted Syrian
entry into Lebanon to stop fighting, provoking longstanding enmity
in Christian right.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MIKHAIL DAHER _ Attorney, originally from northern town of
Kobeyyat. Parliament member from Akkar province in north Lebanon,
now Syrian controlled, since 1972. In 1984 backed attempt by
Damascus government to end war between Moslem and Christian
militias. The United States and Syria's choice of the 58-year-old
Daher for president this month detonated one of the worst political
crises in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SALIM HOSS _ Age 58, professor of economics. Was graduated from
the American University of Beirut and obtained doctorate in
economics from Indiana University in Bloomington, Ind., in 1961.
Chosen premier for the first time by Syrian-backed President Elias
Sarkis in 1976. Distinguished himself as a technocrat who helped
preserve Lebanon's economy and banking system against the ravages
of the civil war. Resigned in 1980 but returned as acting premier
after Prime Minister Rashid Karami was assassinated June 1, 1987.
Advocates ``disciplined liberalism'' and a free-wheeling economic
system. His wife, Leila Pharoun, is Catholic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
