<DOCNO> AP880923-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0813EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SAfrica-PeaceTalks     09-23 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Peace Talks,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Optimistic About Peace Talks On Namibia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha and the U.N.
chief agreed today that independence plans for South-West Africa
are on track, but Botha said the Cuban presence in Angola threatens
a regional peace settlement.
   Botha and U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, who
met for an hour, discussed peace plans for the protracted guerrilla
wars in Angola and South-West Africa, also known as Namibia.
   Perez de Cuellar said the meeting left him ``with a feeling of
relief.''
   ``We are moving forward in a very serious, very effective manner
to implement (U.N.) Resolution 435,'' he said. The resolution
establishes the process leading to Namibian independence.
   ``I think the implementation is closer than ever,'' he added.
   Perez de Cuellar was to fly this afternoon to Angola for talks
with the country's Marxist leaders, who are supported by more than
50,000 Cuban troops.
   Botha said he and Perez de Cuellar agreed on all matters related
to Namibian independence. But Botha added: ``There is a problem.
That is the presence of the Cubans. As soon as we solve that
problem, we will solve the others more easily.'
   South Africa has ruled Namibia _ Africa's last colony _ for 73
years. The United Nations has passed repeated resolutions calling
for independence in the territory.
   South Africa has agreed to end its rule over Namibia and allow
U.N. observers to oversee the transition to independence, but only
if the estimated 50,000 Cuban troops in neighboring Angola withdraw.
   Cuba has agreed in principle to withdraw its troops, but there
is dispute over the timetable. South Africa wants the Cubans out by
June 1, the date it has offered to relinquish control over Namibia.
   The Cubans, meanwhile, reportedly are seeking at least a
two-year period during which to withdraw.
   U.S.-mediated talks involving Angola, Cuba and South Africa,
aimed at setting this timetable, are to resume Monday in
Brazzaville, Congo.
   Perez de Cuellar said he did not feel it was proper for him to
speak to the Cubans about withdrawing from Angola or to get
involved in the Brazzaville talks.
   Botha raised the issue of the Cuban withdrawal at today's
meeting, but gave no public indication he was disappointed by Perez
de Cuellar's reluctance to get more directly involved.
   Botha said South Africa had given approval for a U.N. team to
visit Namibia to assess the tasks that would face a U.N. observer
force.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
