<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0479 09-23 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0479,0675</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede KHAN YUNIS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Peres Leaves for U.S.-Called Session on Mideast Peace</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with today's developments, Peres
leaving for talks with Reagan. Changes byline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres left today for a
meeting with President Reagan on Middle East peace and said Israel
would not negotiate with Palestinians who ``shoot, throw stones or
threaten with terror.''
   Peres' comments came one day after widespread clashes between
Israeli troops and Palestinian rioters in the occupied territories
left 24 Palestinians wounded, according to Arab hospital officials.
   Since the Palestinian uprising began in the occupied lands on
Dec. 8, Israeli soldiers have killed 270 Palestinians. Six Israelis
have died.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin escaped injury Thursday during a
tour of the Gaza Strip town of Khan Yunis when a Palestinian
assailant hurled a chunk of cement from a nearby rooftop. Soldiers
rushed to the site but made no arrests.
   Peres is to meet Monday in New York with Reagan and Foreign
Minister Esmat Abdel Meguid of Egypt.
   The meeting, called by Reagan, caused a political storm in
Israel, where Peres' left-leaning Labor Party and Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc are the two main rivals in
parliamentary elections set for Nov. 1.
   Shamir accused Peres of engineering the session to advance his
party's chances and said such a meeting before the election could
not possibly advance the peace process.
   But Peres said at the airport today the meeting ``has
considerable power to push the peace process forward at a level we
have not seen since the Camp David accords,'' when Israel signed a
peace treaty with Egypt in 1979.
   Peres also said Israel would not negotiate with the Palestine
Liberation Organization or any other Palestinian group that does
not recognize Israel and renounce violence.
   ``Israel will not talk to people who shoot, throw stones or
threaten with terror,'' he said. ``Any state which would like to
participate in the peace process would contribute to peace by
establishing full relations with Israel.''
   Peres, who will make a stopover in Paris, is scheduled to meet
with President Francois Mitterrand and Foreign Minister Roland
Dumas, who will report to Peres on talks last week with PLO chief
Yasser Arafat.
   Peres criticized Dumas for meeting with Arafat. The two met in
Strasbourg, France, where Arafat addressed Socialist members of the
European Parliament last week.
   In another development today, army doctors began vaccinating the
nation's active and reserve duty soldiers in an effort to combat an
outbreak of polio, Health Ministry and army officials said.
   Some police will also receive the vaccine, army radio said.
   Nine polio cases have been confirmed so far in the outbreak,
which took Israeli officials by surprise. The daily Haaretz said
one victim was a 21-year-old soldier from Akko on the northern
Israeli coast.
   On Thursday, the army said four soldiers would face trial in the
beating death of an elderly Palestinian man, Khader al Tarazi, in
Gaza's Jabaliya refugee camp.
   Israel radio said the troops were to be charged with
manslaughter for striking the man with clubs after they broke into
his home Aug. 22 to arrest Palestinian youths suspected of throwing
stones.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus on Thursday, Israeli troops shot
and wounded 16 Palestinians who attacked them with rocks and axes,
Arab hospital officials said. The officials said four other
Palestinians were wounded in clashes in villages near Nablus.
   Hospital officials in the Gaza Strip said four were wounded
there in clashes with troops Thursday, including a 13-year-old boy
who was shot in the chest and rushed to Tel Aviv's Tel Hashomer
hospital in serious condition.
   The army said only 11 Palestinians were wounded in Nablus and
nearby Burka village and three in Gaza.
   Israel captured the West Bank from Jordan and the Gaza Strip
from Egypt during the 1967 Middle East war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
