<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0840EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-DurableGoods     09-23 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Durable Goods,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Orders for Durable Goods Soared 6.0 Percent in August</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders for ``big ticket'' durable goods soared
6.0 percent in August on the strength of big jumps in the military
and transportation sectors, the government said today.
   The Commerce Department said total orders jumped to a seasonally
adjusted $123.1 billion last month. The big jump follows a huge 7.4
percent decline in July, the biggest in more than four years, and
an 8.7 percent increase in June, which was the largest in 30 months.
   Orders for transportation equipment in August were up by 20.9
percent to $35.4 billion. More than half the increase was for motor
vehicles and parts. Auto orders had been weak in July as factories
were switching over to a new model year.
   That follows a 22.4 percent plunge in July and a 33.3 percent
gain in June. The transportation category has been buffeted back
and forth in recent months by big swings in orders for aircraft,
ships and tanks.
   Orders for defense goods jumped 15.3 percent in August to $8.1
billion, following a 49.4 percent drop in July and a 68.3 percent
increase in June. This category, which is also very volatile from
month to month, overlaps transportation and includes military
planes, tanks and ships.
   Excluding defense goods, orders rose 5.4 percent last month
following a decline of 2.2 percent in July and an increase of 4.2
percent in June.
   Excluding transportation, orders rose 1.0 percent in August,
fell 0.9 percent in July and rose 0.7 percent in June.
   Orders in the key category of non-defense capital goods, a good
barometer of business expansion plans, were up 5.4 percent in
August to $38.2 billion, following gains of 2.2 percent in July and
12.5 percent in June. This has been one of the strongest areas of
the economy as manufacturers gear up to meet a boom in export sales.
   Orders for primary metals such as steel fell 1.6 percent in
August, following small declines in July and June.
   Orders for the machinery category which includes computers rose
4.2 percent in August after falling 2.9 percent a month earlier.
Other kinds of electrical machinery were off 0.4 percent after a
3.2 percent gain in July.
   Shipments of durable goods rose 4.4 percent in August to $118.2
billion following a 2.9 percent drop in July.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
