<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0856EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Tibet     09-23 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tibet,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Government Offers Talks With Dalai Lama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chinese government has offered to
hold direct, conditional talks with the exiled Tibetan leader, the
Dalai Lama, at a venue of his choice, the Chinese said in a
statement released in New Delhi today.
   The message was conveyed to the Dalai Lama on Wednesday through
his representative in the Indian capital, a senior Chinese diplomat
said.
   The Buddhist leader has lived in exile in Dharamsala, 300 miles
north of New Delhi in Himachal Pradesh state, since he fled Tibet
in 1959.
   Tsering Tashi, spokesman for the Dalai Lama in Delhi, said the
exiled leader ``has received the invitation for talks and is
deliberating with his advisers on a response.''
   The statement, issued by the Chinese Embassy, offered to hold
talks ``in Beijing, Hong Kong or any of our embassies or consulates
abroad. If the Dalai Lama finds it inconvenient to conduct talks at
these places, he may choose any place he wishes.''
   The Chinese diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
it was the first time his government has given the Dalai Lama a
choice of venues.
   The Chinese condition for talking with the leader of the
Tibetans is that, ``no foreigners should be involved,'' the
statement said.
   The statement said the proposals suggested by the Dalai Lama in
Strasbourg, France, in June ``cannot be considered as the basis for
talks with the (Chinese) central government because it has not at
all relinquished the concept of ``the independence of Tibet.'''
   In a speech delivered to the European Parliament at Strasbourg,
the Dalai Lama asked for ``a self-governing democratic, political
entity'' in Tibet ``in association with the People's Republic of
China.''
   In that speech, the exiled leader for the first time recognized
China's right to handle Tibet's foreign policy and maintain troops
on Tibetan soil.
   The Chinese government statement urged the Dalai Lama to give up
ideas of Tibetan independence.
   ``If the Dalai Lama is ... really concerned for the happiness of
the Tibetan people, for the economic development and prosperity of
the Tibetan nationality, he should truly give up the idea of the
independence of Tibet.''
   Tibetan activists seeking independence have rioted in Lhasa at
least twice in the past year. In March, up to 24 people died in the
province's capital as monks and civilians fought Chinese security
forces. Similar riots in September and October 1987 left 14 people
dead.
</TEXT>
