<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Italy-Ambrosiano     09-23 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy-Ambrosiano,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sources: Indictment Requested In Italian Banking Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PIERO VALSECCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judges investigating Italy's biggest postwar
banking scandal have asked for the indictment of financier Carlo De
Benedetti in connection with the collapse of Banco Ambrosiano,
court officials said today.
   The case of De Benedetti, who has been under investigation for
14 months over the sale of his shares in Banco Ambrosiano just
before it went bankrupt in 1982, also has links with the Institute
for Religious Works, the Vatican bank.
   The Vatican bank was the largest shareholder of Banco
Ambrosiano, which collapsed following the failed repayment of $1.3
billion in Vatican-bank assured loans made to 10 dummy corporations
set up in Latin America.
   Court officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, denied to
specify the charge or charges that De Benedetti faces, other than
to indicate it could include at least one count of extortion.
   GianDomenico Pisapia, De Benedetti's lawyer, said in a statement
there are no grounds for extortion charges against his client.
   Milan judges have been investigating whether De Benedetti
profitted illegally from his investment in the bank once headed by
Roberto Calvi. Calvi's body was found hanging from a London bridge
in June 1982.
   De Benedetti invested $37.1 million for a 2 percent stake in
Banco Ambrosiano before he was appointed deputy chairman of the
bank. He sold the stake when he resigned 65 days later, citing
disagreements with chairman Calvi.
   Court sources indicated De Benedetti is suspected of having
threatened to reveal irregularities in Banco Ambrosiano's
operations.
   If tried and convicted of extortion, De Benedetti could face a
prison sentence of up to 13 years.
   Investigators have asked for indictments, for alleged illegal
financial operations connected with the Ambrosiano case, of
ex-financier Anna Bonomi-Bolchini and Angelo Rizzoli, former
chairman-owner of the Rizzoli publishing group.
   Two Milan judges charged three top-ranking Vatican officials as
being accessories to fraudulent bankruptcy in the bank collapse,
but Italy's highest court last year ruled no action could be taken
against citizens of the Vatican, an independent city-state.
   The Vatican officials are U.S. Archbishop Paul C. Marcinkus,
chairman of the Vatican bank, and two senior executives of the
institute.
</TEXT>
