<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless Shelter,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Advocates Call for More Federal Low-Income Housing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hollywood celebrities, members of Congress and
advocates for the homeless called for more federal low-income
housing money Thursday at the grand opening of a model shelter for
the homeless in the nation's capital.
   ``As nice as this place is, it ain't home,'' said Mitch Snyder,
director of the Federal City Shelter, which is located a half-mile
from the Capitol. ``To have people living in the streets, eating
out of garbage pails is an absolute obscenity. We need housing.''
   Snyder also announced that he and eleven other homeless
advocates from around the country are starting a 48-day hunger
strike to draw attention to the need for low-income housing.
   Snyder used a 51-day hunger strike during the 1984 presidential
campaign to persuade President Reagan to commit federal funds for
the shelter's renovation, then staged a 32-day fast in 1985 when
the administration initially withheld $5 million.
   Others echoed Snyder's call for more money for low-income
housing.
   ``The federal government has to keep its housing promise,'' said
actor Martin Sheen, who played Snyder in a made-for-TV movie called
``The Samaritan.'' ``This is just a stop-gap. What these people
need is houses, apartments they can afford to live in.''
   The housing issue, said Rep. Joe Kennedy, D-Mass., ``is where I
think we will see the major difference between a Republican and
Democratic administration next year.''
</TEXT>
