<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MergerRules     09-23 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Merger Rules,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FTC Considering Changes in Merger Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Trade Commission said Thursday it
will consider easing the rules covering purchases of 10 percent or
less of the stock of a business.
   Currently, federal regulations require that individuals or
businesses planning certain types or mergers or business
acquisitions inform the FTC and the Justice Department in advance
and then wait a specified time before completing the purchase.
   The aim of the rules is to give the two agencies a chance to
block mergers that violate antitrust laws.
   The FTC said it is considering three possible changes in its
rules and is seeking comment from businesses and others interested
in the topic. Any final decision on the matter would also require
agreement of the Justice Department.
   Possible changes include:
   _ Exempting purchases of 10 percent or less of a firm's voting
stock from the notification requirement, on the ground that such
acquisitions are unlikely to violate antitrust laws.
   _ Permitting such purchases, but requiring that the stock be
placed in escrow pending review by the FTC or Justice Department.
   _ Continuing to demand that the potential purchaser notify the
federal agencies, but not requiring it to tell the target company
of its plans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
