<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0048EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-WorldBank-Security     09-23 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World Bank-Security,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Berlin Becomes a `Fortress' for International Finance Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armored cars stood at the ready and an army of
police officers guarded West Berlin Thursday as the World Bank and
International Monetary Fund opened their annual meetings.
   Thousands of protesters were expected to protest what they call
unfair treatment of developing lands by the industrial nations.
   ``My city has become a fortress,'' said a taxi driver, who would
not give his name.
   At about noon an estimated 120 people, some carrying banners,
marched peacefully to protest IMF loans for projects that they said
harm the environment in Third World countries.
   Delegates from the 151 member countries as well as
representatives of banking and industry have been arriving all week
for the talks, which are expected to last a week.
   Leftist militants last Tuesday fired a shotgun at a West German
Finance Ministry official in Bonn, and authorities fear violence
could erupt in the streets of West Berlin.
   A leading West Berlin politician on Wednesday urged organizers
of a massive demonstration planned for Sunday to call off the
protest.
   ``Such a demonstration is in no way useful to the developing
lands,'' said Klaus Landowsky, general secretary of the Christian
Democratic Party of West Berlin.
   Several other protests are scheduled in West Berlin during the
financial talks, and demonstration organizers say they expect up to
40,000 participants.
   Landowsky said demonstration organizers would be culpable ``if
there are violent acts by criminal, autonomous circles'' linked to
the protests.
   Landowsky made the comments at a ceremony opening the first
round of World Bank-IMF talks.
   West Berlin's 6,000-strong police force has been reinforced with
about 2,700 police officers brought in from across West Germany.
   Thousands of green-jacketed police officers, carrying their
sidearms, patrolled the city streets. Armored cars could be seen
off the highway between Tegel Airport and downtown West Berlin.
   Thursday's march was organized by the German Federation for
Environment and the Protection of Nature, one of about 100 groups
planning protest actions during the World Bank-IMF talks.
   Protesters demanding not only that the World Bank and IMF cease
supporting projects that allegedly harm the environment, but also a
general debt forgiveness for those countries.
   According to World Bank figures, the total foreign debt of
developing nations will stand at $1.2 trillion by the end of this
year, an increase of about 4 percent from last year.
   At the sprawling International Congress Center, site of the
talks, delegates and journalists underwent lengthy security checks.
   They were asked to hand over their passports for examination,
empty the contents of their pockets onto a table, run their
portable computers and briefcases through an X-ray machine and walk
through an electronic metal-detector.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
