<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WifeAbortion     09-23 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wife Abortion,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Michigan Supreme Court Upholds Woman's Abortion Right</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Michigan Supreme Court on Thursday let
stand an appeals court order allowing a pregnant woman to have an
abortion over the objections of her estranged husband.
   However, the justices extended until Monday a stay that has
prevented Shawn Lewis, 24, of Flint, from getting an abortion.
   A lawyer for the fetus's court-appointed guardian said he would
file pleadings Friday asking the U.S. Supreme Court to accept an
emergency appeal.
   ``I think the Michigan Court of Appeals is wrong,'' the
attorney, James Bopp Jr. said. ``What we have here is the most
elective of elective abortions. It's our view that Roe did not
legalize abortion on demand.''
   The appeals court said Mrs. Lewis' right to an abortion was
established in the landmark 1973 U.S. Supreme Court decision Roe
vs. Wade.
   The state Supreme Court justices decided they would not tamper
with the intermediate court's action. They did not explain why.
   ``The (U.S.) Supreme Court has to act within 24 hours on an
emergency request. I would imagine that we should be getting a
decision by Monday,'' said Shelley Spivack, one of the volunteer
American Civil Liberties Union attorneys representing Mrs. Lewis.
   In similar cases, the U.S. Supreme Court has denied emergency
appeals, said Spivack, who expects the justices to follow that
precedent.
   ``The law is set right now,'' she said. ``To change it would
require a full hearing before the U.S. Supreme Court and that would
take months and months.''
   ``If they want to revisit the 1976 decision about whether a
husband has veto power over a woman's abortion ... I would hope
they would not do that at Shawn Lewis' expense,'' said Michigan
ACLU executive director Howard Simon.
   Mrs. Lewis is at the end of her first trimester. She became
pregnant after a July 7 reconciliation with her husband. She had
filed for divorce in January and the couple wants to continue
divorce proceedings.
   Her attorneys have said Mrs. Lewis abided by the no-abortion
injunction for fear of jeopardizing her custody of her 16-month-old
child.
   Steven Moss, attorney for the husband Carlton Lewis, said at a
news conference Thursday afternoon in Flint that he had confidence
in the U.S. Supreme Court and expected them to take the appeal.
</TEXT>
