<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0029EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MailboxInspections     09-23 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mailbox Inspections,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Removed 250 Mailboxes After Boy Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE FITZHENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death of a 6-year-old boy who was crushed
by a mailbox not bolted to the ground has led to a nationwide
safety alert and the removal of about 250 unanchored mailboxes in
Maryland and the District of Columbia, a postal service spokesman
said Thursday.
   U.S. Postal Service headquarters issued the alert Wednesday that
mailboxes nationwide should be checked, said Kent Smith, spokesman
for the postal service's Southern Maryland Division office.
   The division launched an inspection Wednesday of 6,000 mailboxes
in the district, Smith said.
   ``After the preliminary count, we had to remove about 5 percent
of the boxes because they were insufficiently anchored. We were
able to fasten down or secure virtually everything else,'' Smith
said. ``About 250 boxes were brought in. All boxes were checked and
those that were not secure and made safe were pulled off the
street.''
   Officials said the 160-pound mailbox that killed Marc Jeffrey
Streidel of Bethesda on Tuesday lacked bolts to anchor it to the
ground.
   Witnesses said the boy had been swinging on the chute when the
mailbox fell over on him.
   Glenn Streidel, Marc's father, said the boy ``was everything you
would want in a son. He was bright, he was very family-oriented, he
loved his sister, he had a leader personality, and he was my little
jock.''
   The mailbox ``wasn't very safe for anybody, especially a little
boy,'' Streidel said.
   ``The feet on these mailboxes are minuscule,'' Streidel said.
``You have a big, bulky box on four tiny feet.''
   Mail carriers are told to notify supervisors if they see that a
mailbox is not securely anchored, Smith said.
   ``Some reports made by neighbors indicated there was a lot of
movement of the box by the kid,'' Smith said. ``The ...
investigation is still reviewing documents and photographs and the
investigation is not complete.''
   Clarence Hoppert, retiring postmaster at the Bethesda Post
Office, told The Washington Post in a story published Thursday that
reports of vandalism are not acted on quickly because of a lack of
staff. Hoppert did not return a telephone message Thursday from The
Associated Press.
   Delays are compounded because the Postal Service's Southern
Maryland Division office has delayed for two years the hiring of a
mechanic in the Bethesda office who would, among other duties,
repair mailboxes, Hoppert said.
   ``The main thing was the safety of the boxes,'' Hoppert said.
   However, Smith said that he doubted what he called Hoppert's
``allegations.''
   ``Most of our carriers have said they don't have any problem
with stability,'' Smith said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
