<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FERCNominations     09-23 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FERC Nominations,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Seals Deal Between Democrats And White House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Energy and Natural Resources
Committee on Thursday approved without dissent and sent to the
floor three nominations to the Federal Energy Commission.
   The action seals a deal between committee Democrats, who were
supported by Republicans, and the White House. The deal puts three
Democrats in the five seats and leaves the chairmanship in
Republican hands.
   The three nominees are Charles Trabandt and Charles Stalon,
currently sitting members of the commission, and Jerry Langdon, a
Midland, Texas, oil and gas consultant.
   Nominations of Martha Hesse, the chairman, and Elizabeth Moller,
a senior lawyer on the committee staff, were approved earlier and
all five are expected to reach the Senate floor as a package.
   Stalon, Ms. Moller and Langdon are Democrats. Stalon, a holdover
whose original term expired in October 1987, will take a vacancy
for a term expiring in October 1989, and Ms. Moller will move into
Stalon's seat for a term expiring in 1991.
   Ms. Hesse, another holdover who has been awaiting confirmation
for more than a year, would sit until 1991. Langdon and Trabandt
would get full terms expiring in 1992.
   The commission regulates interstate oil and gas pipelines and
some natural gas sales from producers to pipelines, licenses
hydroelectric dams and regulates wholesale sales of electricity.
</TEXT>
