<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ArtsGrants     09-23 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arts Grants,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$9 Million Granted to 23 Arts Projects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Endowment for the Arts on Thursday
announced $9 million in matching grants to 23 U.S. organizations.
   The largest, for $1 million, goes to Center Stage Associates
Inc. in Baltimore, for creating a system to pay artists more. The
smallest, two grants for $50,000 each, go to the Coordinating
Council of Literary Magazines in New York and to Monadnock Music in
Peterborough, N.H., the latter to establish a new listeners'
program for children and families.
   The ``Challenge III'' grants are meant to assist model projects
of national significance. They require the organizations to match
each federal dollar with at least $3 in new or increased donations.
   ``Through this new effort, the endowment wants to make a
difference in the arts _ to help launch creative new activities
with potential for long-term benefit to the arts in all sections of
this country,'' said endowment Chairman Frank Hodsoll.
   Challenge I and II grants, during the last decade, were designed
to increase arts organizations' long-term financial stability.
   ``We're particularly excited that so many fields that are
uninstitutionalized, like literature, are getting help from this
program,'' Hodsoll said. ``In the old Challenge program, we gave
money to universities' museums as opposed to the arts education
program Wayne State University is undertaking in Detroit public
schools.
   ``And the American Museum of the Moving Image in New York is
doing a curriculum on the media that can be used in schools,'' he
said.
   Wayne State's grant is $150,000 and the museum's grant is
$300,000.
   Other recipients of grants and amounts are: Ballet West, Salt
Lake City, for touring, $500,000; Bay Area Women's Philharmonic,
San Francisco, to record music by women composers, $85,000;
Brooklyn Academy of Music Inc., $750,000; City Celebration Inc.,
San Francisco, $100,000;
   The Cleveland Foundation, for cooperative programming and
marketing by 18 cultural organizations, $375,000; Council for the
Arts in Westchester, White Plains, N.Y., $100,000; Educational
Broadcasting Corporation-WNET, New York, for a series about
20th-century ballet, $750,000; Foundation for the Joffrey Ballet
Inc., New York, $700,000;
   Kentucky Educational Television, Lexington, to broadcast
regional arts performances, $250,000; the Louisville Orchestra,
$500,000; Maryland State Arts Council, $150,000; the Minnesota
Opera, $150,000; National Trust for Historic Preservation,
Washington, to link architectural preservation with tourism in six
states, $300,000; New England Foundation for the Arts, Cambridge,
Mass., $300,000;
   New York Dance Center, to secure a building for American Ballet
Theater and the Feld Ballet, $900,000; New York Foundation for the
Arts, to increase support for individual artists in seven states,
$800,000; North Carolina Museum of Art, Raleigh, $250,000; the
Pennsylvania Opera Theater, Philadelphia, to produce opera in
community residencies, $60,000; Southern Arts Federation Inc.,
Atlanta, to develop rural and minority arts, $100,000, and
University of Wyoming Art Museum, Laramie, for a new building,
$400,000.
</TEXT>
