<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MinorMovies     09-23 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Minor Movies,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Bambi' Meets `Nightmare On Elm Street'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A survey of 1,000 elementary and junior
high school students found their favorite movies to be ``Nightmare
on Elm Street'' and ``Friday the 13th.''
   The survey, conducted by the Junior League of Charleston, also
found that while such violent R-rated movies generally are rented
by adults, children manage to get access to them and prefer them to
movies targeted at their age groups.
   ``The results of this study suggest that adults rent R-rated
slasher films,'' a report on the study said. ``It does not
conclusively indicate that they rent those films for minors, but
minors are viewing them.''
   Rene McEldowney, a Marshall University statistics professor who
headed the project, said the league has begun to place posters in
video stores that explain the movie ratings system. The league also
hopes to organize groups of seven to 10 people to discuss the issue
of slasher movies.
   ``I don't think parents are uncaring or malicious. It's just
that they're in a hurry, and they don't have time to review the
contents of each movie they rent for their children,'' said Paula
Flaherty of the Junior League.
   Eighty-nine percent of the Kanawha County junior high students
surveyed recently said they watched ``Nightmare,'' while 77 percent
of the elementary students surveyed reported that they had seen it.
   For ``Friday the 13th,'' 86 percent of the junior high students
said they had seen it, compared to 66 percent of the elementary
students.
   Wes Bruce, director of research for the county school system,
said the actual number of students watching these movies probably
was slightly lower. Peer pressure and other factors could have
influenced children to report that they had seen these movies when
they actually hadn't, he said.
   ``But the point is the same,'' Bruce said. ``These movies are
readily accessible, and accessibility is only going to increase.''
   Of all the students surveyed, ``Nightmare'' was ranked as the
most popular and ``Friday the 13th'' placed second, followed by
``Predator'' and ``Dirty Dancing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
