<2ND_LINE>AM-Distraught Driver,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Driver Douses Deputies, Threatens To Set Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man distraught over his car being
towed doused himself and two deputies with gasoline Thursday and
threatened to flick a cigarette lighter before being overpowered by
one of the officers, police said.
   James Stephens of Charleston was sent to the Weston State
Hospital for psychiatric observation after the incident in front of
the federal building downtown, sheriff's Sgt. Jim Chadwick said.
   Stephens had left a car unattended after it ran out of gas,
Chadwick said. When he returned with several gallons of gasoline in
a bucket, his car was hooked to a tow truck, the sergeant said.
   ``His car had run out of gas and when he got back to it, it was
being towed away,'' Chadwick said. ``He just lost his marbles.''
   Stephens chased the driver of the tow truck and began arguing
with him, Chadwick said. He then lay down on the sidewalk in front
of the federal building with the gasoline beside him.
   Chadwick and Deputy A.B. Burke approached, and Stephens soaked
the three with gasoline and threatened to light the lighter,
Chadwick said.
   ``One little spark and we'd have had a great big fireball,''
Chadwick said. ``The man intended to do harm to himself and
others.''
   Chadwick tried for about 15 minutes to talk the man into giving
up the lighter. While he spoke to the man, Burke approached from
the other side and grabbed the hand holding the lighter. The three
then were washed with water before Stephens was taken away in an
ambulance.
</TEXT>
