<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PoisonMushrooms     09-23 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poison Mushrooms,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Official Still Critical After Mushroom Poisoning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese education official who ate soup
made from poisonous mushrooms remained hospitalized in critical
condition Thursday, officials said.
   Zhangjian Chen, 37, from the University of Beijing in China, has
not shown signs of recovery, but his condition didn't appear to be
worsening, said Yang Shiqi, a spokesman for the Consulate-General
of China.
   Chen's colleague, Lilly You, 32, who also ate the soup, was in
satisfactory condition Thursday.
   The pair were invited to this country about a month ago by
officials of the Baker and Taylor Co. of Bridgewater, N.J., a
wholesale book company owned by W.R. Grace & Co. of New York.
   Chris Tofalli, a spokesman for Grace, said they are looking at
libraries.
   The two, who are based in New York, apparently had been visiting
acquaintances in the Stamford area and had gone hiking Friday,
officials said. They picked four mushrooms, and made soup for
lunch, Stamford Hospital officials said.
   Late Friday, they started experiencing abdominal cramping,
nausea and vomiting, and were hospitalized early Saturday, said Dr.
Stuart Waldstreicher, who is treating them.
   The mushrooms were probably of the amanita virosa family of
highly toxic mushrooms popularly known as the ``Destroying Angel''
found in wooded areas throughout the Northeast from late June until
November, Waldstreicher said.
</TEXT>
