<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ComputerSecurity     09-23 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Computer Security,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Agencies Find Computer Systems Need Security Measures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agencies have identified more than
53,000 government computer systems that require security measures
because they contain sensitive data, officials told Congress on
Thursday.
   Identifying the systems handling sensitive but unclassified
information is among a series of steps _ including improved
training programs for computer users _ mandated under the Computer
Security Act signed into law by President Reagan early this year.
   ``It appears that federal agencies are attempting to comply with
the act,'' the General Accounting Office said in a report presented
to a House Science subcommittee by Howard Rhile, associate director
of the GAO's information management and technology division.
   The GAO, an investigative arm of Congress, said that as of Sept.
8, 74 out of 84 agencies surveyed reported they had identified all
sensitive computer systems under their jurisdiction.
   It said 72 of the 74 agencies saying they had identified all
sensitive systems reported the number of systems involved. For the
72 agencies, the total came to 53,443 computer systems.
   ``Defense agencies reported an estimated 52,000 sensitive
systems or about 97 percent of the total number reported by all
agencies,'' the GAO said.
   For the defense agencies, the breakdown was: Navy, 27,000
systems; Army, 12,000; Air Force, 10,000; other Pentagon computer
systems, 3,000.
   Jay Plager, an official from the Office of Management and
Budget, told the panel that federal agencies have made a ``good
start'' in moving to implement the legislation, which calls for
agencies to submit detailed computer security plans by Jan. 8, 1989.
   ``We believe that the act gives us a framework and provides the
momentum for the government to address the security of federal
computer systems,'' he said in testimony before the transportation,
aviation and materials subcommittee.
   Plager said that in planning the security measures, OMB
officials have been working closely with the National Institute for
Standards and Technology, the National Security Agency and the
Office of Personnel Management.
   The importance of adequate computer security, he said, is
pointed up by the fact that ``next year the federal government will
invest more than $17 billion in building and maintaining federal
information technology systems _ systems which are critical to
every major activity of our government.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
