<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ArmsSale     09-23 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arms Sale,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Approves Weapons Sales To South Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon notified Congress on Thursday it
had approved three different arms sales to South Korea involving
reconnaissance jets, aircraft spare parts and Sparrow air-to-air
missiles.
   Combined, the three sales total $238 million, the Pentagon added.
   Assuming there are no congressional objections, the Defense
Department said the South Koreans would be sold 12 RF-4C
reconnaissance jets with radar-jamming capability at a cost of $138
million.
   The jets will be drawn from ``excess Air National Guard stocks''
and the Westinghouse Electric Corp. of Baltimore will provide the
radar-jamming pods, the Pentagon said. The U.S. Air Force will
oversee that transaction.
   In addition, South Korea will be sold spare sparts at a cost of
$79 million to support six types of U.S.-made aircraft already in
its inventory. The parts will be used for C-123K, F-4, F-5, T-33,
F-16 and A-T-37 aircraft and the Air Force will oversee the deal.
   The Koreans also will be offered 76 AIM-7F Sparrow air-to-air
missiles for their jet fighters at an estimated cost of $21
million, the Pentagon concluded. The U.S. Navy will oversee that
sale, for which the prime contractors will be the General Dynamics
Corp. and the Raytheon Co.
</TEXT>
