<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FordAerospace     09-23 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ford Aerospace,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company To Pay $7 Million To Settle Claims on Air Force Equipment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Aerospace Corp. of Newport Beach, Calif.,
will pay the government $7 million to settle claims that the
company submitted false pricing data for bombing equipment sold to
the Air Force, the Justice Department announced Thursday.
   The false pricing allegations relate to three 1981 contracts for
the sale of Pave Tack pods, which are mounted on aircraft and,
through the use of lasers and computers, enable the aircraft to
guide bombs to targets.
   In a settlement agreement, the Justice Department alleged that
Ford certified and submitted cost or pricing information during
negotiations which was not accurate, complete or current.
   Using such data amounted to defective pricing, the government
said, causing the Air Force to rely on inaccurate information,
leading to possible overpricing of the pods.
   Ford will pay $7 million to the government within 30 days under
the terms of the agreement.
   The company also must absorb all of the expenses, including
legal costs, which it incurred in connection with the government's
audits and investigations, the Justice Department said in a
statement.
</TEXT>
