<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PanAm-Engine     09-23 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pan Am-Engine,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Investigators Search For Clues In Flying Engine Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators examined a Pan Am
Express commuter plane Thursday after an engine exploded in flight
and sent flying debris into the passenger cabin, injuring nine
people.
   The four-engine, 50-seat DeHavilland-7 turboprop was carrying 13
passengers and three crew members Wednesday night from New York
City's Kennedy airport when the explosion occurred 13 miles from
Albany County Airport.
   The explosion was in the No. 2 engine, on the inside left-hand
side of the plane, Pan Am Express spokeswoman Pamela Hanlon said.
   Since the plane already had started its landing approach, it was
at a low altitude and there was no depressurization from debris
puncturing the fuselage, said Kathleen Bergen, a spokeswoman for
the Federal Aviation Administration.
   The injured, including one flight attendant, were treated at
Albany Medical Center Hospital, spokesman Richard Puff said.
   All but one were treated and discharged. Steven Roecker, 33, of
Rexford was in fair condition Thursday with eye and facial
injuries, Puff said.
   The National Transportation Safety Board took over the
investigation Thursday, and a final report on the accident is not
expected for eight to nine months, said Alan Yurman, a board
spokesman in New York City.
   Hanlon said the approximately nine-year-old plane was to be
flown without passengers back to the company's headquarters in
Philadelphia late Thursday or early Friday.
</TEXT>
