<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Preston-Execution     09-23 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Preston-Execution,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Denies Stay For Killer Scheduled To Die Next Tuesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Asociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted killer Robert Preston,
scheduled to die next week for stabbing a convenience store clerk
10 years ago, lost an appeal Thursday in the Florida Supreme Court.
   Preston, 31, is under his second death warrant for the Jan. 9,
1978, murder of Earline Walker, whose body was found with 20 stab
wounds, a slashed throat and a cross cut into her forehead.
   She was on duty during a late-night shift at a convenience store
in Forest City when Preston entered and robbed her of $574 at
knifepoint, according to court records. He then forced her into her
car, drove about 1{ miles and took her to a field where he forced
her to disrobe and then stabbed her, the records said. Her nude and
mutilated body was found later that day.
   In addition to his murder conviction and capital sentence handed
down in 1981, Preston was sentenced to life in prison for
kidnapping and 15 years for robbery.
   The Supreme Court rejected arguments that Preston's execution
should be delayed so that new evidence could be considered. Preston
planned to appeal next to U.S. District Court in Orlando, said
Larry Spalding, head of the agency that represents indigent
death-row inmates.
   Preston is scheduled to die in the state's electric chair at
Florida State Prison Tuesday morning.
   Six other death-row inmates are under death warrants in Florida.
Nine had been facing execution, but stays granted earlier this
month halted the executions of Stephen Todd Booker and Freddie Lee
Hall, who had been scheduled to die earlier this week.
   He would be the 18th prisoner executed in Florida and the 102nd
nationally since the 1976 U.S. Supreme Court ruling allowing states
to resume use of the death penalty.
</TEXT>
