<HEAD>Suicide Suspected In Family's Second Death In A Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIVER HILLS, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A millionaire businessman was found
dead Thursday near the suburban mansion where his estranged wife
was killed last week and his death was being investigated as a
suicide, authorities said.
   The body of Daniel Giwosky, 51, was found at the end of a
driveway of a neighbor's home. The medical examiner's office in
Milwaukee said he suffered a single gunshot wound to the head.
   Milwaukee County District Attorney E. Michael McCann said a gun
was found next to Giwosky's body and that preliminary indications
suggested the death was a suicide.
   On Friday, Giwosky told police he found the body of his wife,
Judith, 46, at the foot of the basement stairs in her home.
   A medical examiner's report said an autopsy showed evidence of
``crushing neck and traumatic head injuries,'' but further tests
were being done to pinpoint the cause of death.
   Giwosky, president of Fox Bay Co., which owns as many as 300
properties in Milwaukee's inner city, told police he found his wife
after going to the home to do laundry.
   He said the stairs leading to the basement were covered with
water because his wife had been cleaning them.
   He told police he changed his clothes and washed up after
cleaning up a large quantity of blood around the body.
Blood-stained trousers and a towel were found in the guest house.
   Police said Judith Giwosky called police just hours before her
death asking that a squad car drive by her home because she had
filed for divorce and had obtained a court order to keep her
husband out of the residence.
   Giwosky had been living in a guest house on the estate.
   No charges have been filed in Mrs. Giwosky's death.
