<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MinisterTrial     09-23 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Minister Trial,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Felt He `Didn't Want To Live,' Killer Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A minister sobbed Thursday while
describing how he shot to death and then decapitated a church
handyman to fake his own death in a scheme inspired by an
advertisement in Soldier of Fortune magazine.
   John David Terry was found guilty Thursday of first-degree
murder and arson in the death of handyman James Chester Matheny. He
later took the stand in a hearing to decide whether he should be
sentenced to death for the June 15, 1987, killing.
   The minister said an advertisement in the magazine made him
believe he could begin a new life by assuming the name of a dead
person.
   ``I just reached a point in my life that I didn't want to
live,'' Terry said. ``I just felt I was going crazy, losing my
mind.''
   Prosecutor John Zimmermann said Terry embezzled church money and
his plan was foiled only because firefighters arrived before
Matheny's body, left in the burning church's attic, was burned
beyond recognition.
   A medical examination determined the body was not Terry's.
   Terry, former pastor of the Emmanuel Church of Christ Oneness
Pentecostal, told the jury he was severely depressed following his
mother's death in 1983 and took out an insurance policy because he
was going to commit suicide.
   ``I reached a point in my ministry, I just felt like a complete
failure,'' Terry testified. ``The church wasn't growing and I
thought it was my fault.''
   Terry said he decided to leave the ministry. But when part-time
work selling aluminum siding didn't help, he got to the point where
he had difficulty talking to people, Terry said.
   That was when he spotted the magazine for military buffs. ``It
just jumped out of that page ... How to get lost ... How to
disappear,'' Terry said. ``It was something that began to feed a
person looking for an escape.''
   Terry testified that he tried to obtain birth certificates and
identification in the name of a deceased childhood friend. When
that failed, he went to the library and reviewed old newspaper
stories seeking an identity. One story told of a 7-year-old boy who
had drowned with his father on a fishing trip.
   Witnesses testified during the trial that Terry obtained a
driver's license and Social Security card under the name of Jerry
Winston Milom, who died at age 7 in 1951.
   ``I was functioning on the outside, but inside I was going
through hell, pure hell,'' Terry said. ``I couldn't reach out to
anyone. I was trying to work it out. I worked it out, but I worked
it out in the wrong way.''
   Terry testified that he was a ``failure at everything.
   ``I was even a failure at trying to take my own life. Every time
I tried to pull the trigger my mother's face would come up and I
couldn't pull the trigger,'' he said, sobbing. ``I knew I would
never see her again if I did that.''
</TEXT>
