<HEAD>Police Union Offers To Pay For Cars Damaged During Wet T-Shirt
Contest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police union Thursday offered to pay
for damage that apparently occurred at its big annual picnic when
people jumped on top of patrol cars to view a wet T-shirt contest
among female officers.
   Damage to the six vehicles was estimated at less than $10,000,
according to Sgt. Scott O'Mara, a state police spokesman.
   Neither O'Mara nor the union would confirm the report of the
contest, published in Thursday's edition of The Hartford Courant.
   ``We now have started six separate investigations to determine
the exact circumstances. We'll have to take it from there,'' said
O'Mara.
   The Connecticut State Police Union said in a statement issued
late Thursday that it would pay even though it maintained no
Connecticut troopers caused any damage. The union was host to 1,800
active and retired state police officers from seven states at the
Sept. 14 picnic at Mountainside Park in Wallingford.
   The picnic is an annual event rotated among states and is
sponsored by a national police organization, Robert Kowalczyk,
president of the Connecticut State Police Union, told the newspaper.
   At the time he was interviewed by the Courant, Kowalczyk denied
that any damage was done at the picnic and said he had no knowledge
that a wet T-shirt contest was held.
   ``We had arm wrestling and a road race. There was baseball, but
that (a wet T-shirt contest) would not have been a sanctioned
event,'' Kowalczyk said.
   The newspaper quoted a picnic-goer who spoke only if guaranteed
anonymity as saying the contest was organized by a member of an
out-of-state department following an afternoon of beer drinking.
   The out-of-state officer used the park's public-address system
to speak glowingly of the female officers of his department and
challenged all comers to match their physiques, the witness said.
   Kowalczyk was not at union headquarters Thursday and couldn't be
reached for comment, secretaries at his office told The Associated
Press.
   The union said in it statement that it would seek to make
responsible parties reimburse it for the costs.
   Forst said he was pleased with the union's decision and said it
showed responsible leadership.
