<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Burundi     09-23 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Burundi,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressional Panel Favors Pressure for Probe and Swift Justice in
Burundi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional panel Thursday recommended
linking U.S. and World Bank aid to Burundi to that country's
efforts to end ethnic discrimination and willingness to allow
international investigation into tribal massacres that claimed up
to 20,000 lives last month.
   A resolution threatening suspension of U.S. aid after six months
and U.S. opposition to World Bank assistance after a year was
adopted on a voice vote by the House Foreign Affairs subcommittee
on Africa.
   ``All countries must be made to understand that if their armed
forces kill civilians, there will be repercussions in their
relations with the United States,'' Rep. William Gray, D-Pa.,
asserted in support of the legislation introduced by Rep. Ted
Weiss, D-N.Y.
   Gray was referring to revenge slayings of an estimated
5,000-20,000 Hutu tribespeople in mid-August by Burundi soldiers
who belong mainly to the Tutsi tribe, a minority that has dominated
the Central African country for generations. More than 60,000 Hutus
fled to neighboring Rwanda, the panel was told.
   The Burundi army was responding to the massacre of an estimated
2,000-3,000 people, many of them Tutsis, in a preemptive attack by
majority Hutus. They reportedly feared the Tutsis were planning a
repetition of the 1972 slaying of 100,000-200,000 Huus in one of
modern Africa's bloodiest episodes.
   The United States in early August launched a $4.5 million
five-year population control program for Burundi, in addition to
$5.2 million in 1988 economic aid for health, rural development and
environment programs.
   Burundi is to draw $80 million in grants and concessional loans
from the World Bank this year, making it the largest per capita
recipient of such low-interest credit, Weiss said.
   State Department witnesses at the joint hearing of the Africa
and human rights subcommittees backed the resolution's intent. But
they voiced misgivings that setting deadlines could undermine
efforts of President Pierre Buyoya to promote equality in Burundi
and punish wrongdoing despite resistance by extremists among the
ruling Tutsis.
   Buyoya came to power in a bloodless coup a year ago, and ``it is
sadly ironic that these tragic events should have taken place under
... a government committed to policy reform and ethnic
reconciliation,'' said Kenneth L. Brown, deputy assistant secretary
of state for African affairs.
   ``The difference is tremendous'' between the Buyoya government
and previous Burundi regimes, Brown said. ``We feel this is a man
who is on the right track and should be supported against those who
would act against the interests of the Burundian people.''
   ``Those are noble words, but actions speak louder than words,''
said Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind. ``I suggest our State Department
convey to Burundi that ... if officers engaged in genocide, they
should be brought to justice expeditiously.''
   Buyoya has ruled out investigation by international bodies of
what he says is an internal Burundian problem.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
