<DOCNO> AP880923-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0229EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vatican-Women     09-23 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vatican-Women,0630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Papal Document Rules Out Women Priests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major Vatican document scheduled for release this
month rules out priesthood for women but calls for greater respect
for them, a Vatican official said Thursday.
   The document on the ``Dignity of Woman,'' due to be made public
Sept. 30, breaks little new ground, the official said.
   The Roman Catholic Church has always barred women from the
priesthood but Pope John Paul II recently increased his efforts to
promote respect for women.
   The Vatican's limitations on women have been one of the most
vexing issues for the church in the United States and Western
Europe. The official, who is familiar with the document and spoke
on condition of anonymity, conceded that it will disappoint some
women.
   The official said the pope's document was very ``personal'' and
called it a ``theological, anthropological meditation on the
meaning of Christian womanhood.''
   The document says women cannot be priests because Jesus did not
choose them for such a role during his lifetime.
   The pope rejected the argument that Jesus was influenced by
sociological factors such as the low status of women at the time.
   The Italian news agency AGI, which said it had access to the
document, quoted it as saying:
   ``When Christ called only men to be his apostles, he did it in a
totally free and sovereign way. He did it with the same liberty
with which in all his acts he recognized the dignity and vocation
of women, without conforming to the dominant practice and the
tradition embodied in the legislation of his time.''
   John Paul went on to say that Jesus reserved for men the most
important priestly duty, the consecration of the Eucharist, thus
indicating they only should be priests, according to the AGI report.
   Under the Catholic faith, consecration transforms bread into the
Eucharist, or body of Jesus, during the Mass.
   ``If Christ, in instituting the Eucharist, linked it in such an
explicit manner to the priestly service of the Apostles, it is
right to think that by this he wanted to express the relation
between man and woman, that is what is `feminine' and what is
`masculine,' intended by God both in the mystery of creation and in
the mystery of the redemption,'' the pope wrote, according to AGI.
   The pope has said repeatedly that the all-male priesthood is a
result of Jesus' designs for the church, rather than discrimination.
   In a draft letter issued in April, Roman Catholic bishops in the
United States recommended that the church study the possibility of
installing women as permanent deacons _ a step below priesthood.
American bishops have been among the strongest supporters of an
expanded role for women.
   In the new document, John Paul criticizes discrimination against
women, saying ``the truth revealed in the creation of human beings
... constitutes the principal argument against situations that are
objectively damaging or unjust,'' AGI reported.
   But he says men and women are different by nature, with neither
gender's characteristics superior, the AGI report said.
   ``Women, in the name of liberation from the `domination' of men,
should not try to appropriate masculine characteristics that do not
correspond with their own original femininity,'' he wrote,
according to AGI.
   ``There exists a well-founded fear that further down this road,
women won't `realize themselves,' and instead will deform and lose
that which constitutes their essential richness.''
   The Vatican official said the document repeats the pope's
support for women who want to raise children full-time, instead of
working outside the house.
   It also asks men to reflect on whether they see their wives as
sex objects rather than partners.
</TEXT>
