<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RandomShootings     09-23 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Random Shootings,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Distraught Man With Pet Alligator Wounds Six, Kills Self</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA METZLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who wounded six people and killed
himself during a shooting spree apparently was upset about a
neighborhood cat that devoured rabbits he raised to feed to a pet
alligator, officials said Thursday.
   Victims of the 100-round shooting frenzy included an
18-month-old boy hit by flying glass and bullet fragments.
   Two people were seriously wounded, including a man shot in the
chest and a woman shot in the face, said Lt. Randy Mancini.
   Shots were first reported fired in the Palms district around
11:15 p.m. Wednesday, and continued until about 1 a.m. Thursday.
   Officers found the gunman, John Wise, 38, dead, apparently of a
self-inflcted gunshot, shortly before 4 a.m., Mancini said. The
body was inside a shed housing a penned-off pond that was home to a
small alligator, Mancini said.
   A MAC-10 machine pistol was found along with 14 weapons, but was
not believed to have been used, said Detective Lee Kingsford.
   Derrek Brown, supervising animal control officer in the West Los
Angeles animal shelter, said Wise called Wednesday, complaining
about a cat who had been eating ``a total of about 100 rabbits over
three years,'' and wanting to know if he could shoot it.
   Brown told him it was illegal to discharge a firearm in the city.
   ``He was pretty upset,'' Brown said. ``He was just fed up.''
   The man calmed down and was told an officer would investigate
this week or next, Brown said.
   The rabbits, left to run free in the yard along with some ducks,
were raised to feed the alligator, he said.
   Police said they doubted the missing rabbits were solely
responsible for triggering the shooting. Neighhors said Wise, who
lived alone, also was upset over a separation from his wife.
   Police said Wise started shooting at cars on a busy road near
his home, and injured people in three vehicles. He also fired shots
at police helicopters, but did not strike them.
   No shots were fired at police on the ground, nor did police fire
at Wise, Mancini said.
</TEXT>
