<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland     09-23 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Politburo Warns Against Efforts to Derail Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ruling Politburo of the Communist
Party warned Thursday against attempts to undermine the
``partner-like trustworthiness'' established in talks this month
between the authorities and the opposition.
   The Politburo met Tuesday, one day after the government of Prime
Minister Zbigniew Messner resigned under fire for mishandling the
economy.
   A Politburo statement issued Thursday made no comment on the
resignation, saying only that the Politburo discussed the decisions
of parliament.
   It urged participants to refrain from disclosing details of
meetings held in preparation for the round-table talks the
government has promised on the future of the banned trade union
movement Solidarity.
   ``All attempts to establish accomplished facts, provoke emotions
during different meetings, publicize with the help of foreign mass
media a biased picture of talks affect this cause and undermine the
partner-like trustworthiness,'' the statement said.
   It appeared to refer to a detailed account given by Wladyslaw
Frasyniuk to Western reporters Saturday on the third meeting among
Solidarity leader Lech Walesa; Solidarity and official union
activists, and Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak.
   Frasyniuk is a Solidarity regional leader from Wroclaw.
   The issue of trade unions has been the main topic of debate in
talks between Walesa and Kiszczak prompted by August strikes, the
worst labor unrest in seven years.
   At a meeting Sept. 16, Walesa and Kiszczak agreed that
round-table talks would begin in mid-October.
   The party, at a plenum on Aug. 27-28, appeared to exclude the
possibility of two trade unions operating in a single plant. The
party has not spelled out its policy on trade union reform,
although it now appears that changes may be possbile.
   ``At present, of special significance for the labor movement is
further improvement of its model and structure. This should be
favored by the amendments to the law on trade unions,'' the
Politburo said Thursday.
   Party leader Wojciech Jaruzelski criticized the government at
the plenum during the strike wave. At the meeting, Jaruzelski said
the government's future would be decided at this month's meeting of
parliament.
   A new government will be named Sept. 27, the state-run news
agency PAP announced earlier.
</TEXT>
