<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDS-SouthernBaptists     09-23 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Southern Baptists,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Southern Baptists Stop Distributing AIDS Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Southern Baptist social-concerns arm
has decided to quit distributing the Surgeon General's Report on
AIDS, which calls for stepped-up sex education in schools.
   The denomination's Chistian Life Commission, which lately has
come under fundamentalist control as have most denominational
agencies, took the action last week without discussion, Baptist
Press reports.
   However, the commissioner who moved the action, Ruth Morgan of
Bartlesville, Okla., said the report prepared by U.S. Surgeon
General C. Edward Koop fails to mention morals or a sense of right
and wrong in sex.
   ``We're going for total abstinence,'' she said. ``No pamphlet
printed or mailed by the Christian Life Commission should promote
anything except sex within marriage.''
   Concerning the report's advocacy of the use of condoms to
prevent AIDS, she said, ``There is no mention of condom-failure
rate. They are saying now it could be as high as 30 percent to 50
percent in homosexual activity.''
   The commission, which recently had a turnover in administration,
also decided to drop a pamphlet that favors abolition of capital
punishment.
</TEXT>
