<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gibraltar-IRA     09-23 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gibraltar-IRA,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness Says British Commandos Shot At IRA Members on Ground</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GIBRALTAR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A witness to the March shooting deaths of three
unarmed IRA members on Thursday said one of the agents raised her
hands in surrender but British commandos kept shooting after she
and another agent fell to the ground.
   A third Irish Republican Army member a short distance away also
was shot and killed in the March 6 incident.
   
   Maxie Proetta told an inquest he was looking out a window of his
first-floor apartment when he saw several men follow and then open
fire on a woman and a man, later identified as IRA members Mairead
Farrell, 31, and Daniel McCann, 31.
   ``Before the shots, the girl went like this,'' he said, putting
his hands up by his head.
   Proetta said Farrell fell to the ground after the firing began.
   ``The men were still pointing at the bodies and I heard a few
shots,'' Proetta told the court. ``I thought they were firing at
the bodies on the ground.''
   His testimony came on the 13th day of an inquest by Gibraltar
Coroner Felix Pizzarello and an 11-man jury into the shooting
deaths Ms. Farrell, McCann and Sean Savage, 24, who were suspected
of planting a car bomb in the British colony at Spain's southern
tip.
   The inquest has no power of prosecution. Its aim is to determine
whether the police action was lawful.
   On Wednesday, Josephine Celecia, also a Gibraltar resident, said
she witnessed the shooting of Farrell and McCann and believed the
man who shot them kept shooting after they fell to the ground
wounded.
   Critics of British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government
have claimed the shootings are evidence of an unofficial
``shoot-to-kill'' policy against members of the IRA.
   The IRA is fighting to end British rule of the
Protestant-majority Northern Ireland and unite it with the Roman
Catholic Irish republic.
   Seven Special Air Service (SAS) commandos and several British
intelligence officers have testified they believed the three IRA
members were armed and dangerous and on a mission to set off a car
bomb in Gibraltar by a radio-control device when they were shot.
   The commandos have testified they had planned to arrest the
three but opened fire when Farrell and McCann made threatening
movements. They pumped more than two dozen bullets into the bodies
of the three IRA members.
   Savage parked a car a car in Gibraltar hours before the
shootings, but neither it nor another IRA car found across the
border into Spain contained a bomb.
   Days later, Spanish police located a third car packed with 141
pounds of explosives and a timing device in the nearby resort of
Marbella.
   While the three proved to be unarmed, the IRA acknowledged they
were on ``active service,'' meaning they were on a mission to
strike at British targets.
</TEXT>
