<2ND_LINE>AM-Evangelist-Sodomy,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Evangelist Convicted Of Sodomy; Still Faces Federal Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evangelist Mario ``Tony'' Leyva was convicted
Thursdasy of sodomizing two teen-age boys and said he accepted the
verdict as the will of God.
   Jurors deliberated 3{ hours before convicting Leyva of
sodomizing one teen-age boy in 1984 and another in 1987.
   The preacher told reporters while the jury was deliberating that
the trial was part of the chaos that will fill the world as it
nears its end.
   Some of Leyva's supporters wept as the verdicts were read, but
the minister, who had maintained his innocence, showed no emotion.
   Leyva, who also faces a federal charges of using his traveling
ministry to transport male minors with the intent to engage in
criminal sexual activity and prostitution, accepted the verdict as
God's will.
   ``God's been good to me,'' said Levya, who faces a maximum
penalty of 10 years in prison. ``He's never let me down. I don't
know what he's got in mind, but he won't let me down.''
   During the two-day trial, both victims testified against the
preacher. The prosecution also called four other witnesses who
claimed they had been molested by Leyva as far back as 1967, even
though he was not charged in those cases.
   The jury recommended a prison sentence of 2{ years. Roanoke
County Circuit Judge Kenneth E. Trabue set sentencing for Oct. 26
and freed Leyva on $10,000 bond.
   Leyva testified that he had slept in the same motel bed with
each of the boys he was accused of sodomizing, but he denied they
had sex.
   The victims testified that Leyva had taken sexual advantage of
them dozens of times after their parents had allowed them to spend
the night with the preacher.
   Defense attorney Harry F. Bosen Jr. called more than a dozen
witnesses who asserted that Leyva was not known to be a child
molester or a homosexual.
   Leyva faces trial next month on the federal charges of using
boys in an interstate prostitution ring. He faces up to 65 years in
prison and $550,000 in fines.
   Two of his followers also are charged in that case. Organist
Rias Edward Morris faces 45 years and $530,000 in fines and Freddie
M. Herring faces up to 25 years in prison and $510,000 in fines.
   Leyva said the charges have hurt his Tony Leyva Evangelistic
Association Inc.
   He said the Columbus, Ga.-based ministry was ``$75,000 in the
red. We've lost our television and radio ministry. It's affected
the credibility and faith of many church folks.''
