<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama     09-23 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Ambassador to U.S. Released; Opposition Activist Detained</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former foreign minister and
ambassador to the United States was released from armed forces
custody, but an opposition activist was arrested Thursday by
security agents and charged with subversion.
   Dominador Bazaan, the former minister, said his six-day
detention was politically motivated and stemmed from his close
relations with deposed President Eric Arturo Delvalle.
   Police and security agents meanwhile arrested opposition
activist Alberto Conte and took over Conte's publicity firm in the
capital, witnesses said.
   Lawmakers allied with Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, commander of
Panama's Defense Forces and the country's de facto ruler, ousted
Delvalle Feb. 26 after Delvalle tried to fire the general. Noriega
is under U.S. indictment on drug trafficking charges.
   Bazaan, 50, said he received ``correct treatment'' while
detained at Panama City's Modelo Prison, where he shared a cell
with eight common criminals.
   He said he was released Wednesday night after relatives paid
$10,000 bail.
   Bazaan, who served as ambassador in Washington from September
1985 to February 1987, said he still considered Delvalle ``the
president (of Panama), but this has its limitations.'' He said he
had had no personal contact with Delvalle since Feb. 26 and has
made no effort to find him.
   Delvalle went into hiding after his ouster. The United States
still recognizes him as Panama's legitimate president.
   A government official who spoke on condition of anonymity said
Conte, a leader of the opposition National Civic Crusade protest
movement, was charged with engaging in activities against state
security.
   The Defense Forces had no comment about the arrest.
   Employees of Conte's firm said the agents confiscated documents
and disconnected telephones at the offices.
   Conte, also president of Panama's journalists' college, was
jailed for eight days in October last year in connection with his
opposition activities.
   The National Civic Crusade, a coalition of professional,
business and labor groups, staged numerous protests last year
calling on Noriega to resign.
</TEXT>
