<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     09-23 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The oil futures market has gained more strength
in anticipation of this weekend's OPEC price committee meeting.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the November contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, settled
9 cents higher at $14.65 a barrel Thursday. Other contract months
also were higher at the close.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for October delivery gained 0.50
cent to close at 45.85 cents a gallon, while other contract months
closed mixed.
   The October wholesale heating oil contract lost 0.03 cent to
settle at 41.06 cents a gallon. Other heating oil contracts settled
mostly higher.
   Analysts said the market continued firming in anticipation of
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries' price monitoring
committee meeting scheduled for Sunday and Monday.
   ``Although there's no overreaction, there's a firm undertone on
the possibility that there might be some news from OPEC,'' said
Chris McCormack a trader with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   U.S. market prices were aided early in the day by reports of a
fire on an oil drilling platform in the North Sea, but slacked off
on news that the blaze was under control, analysts said.
   But the market's overall strength continued to be OPEC-related,
analysts said.
   ``The market is showing very rational behavior to not react to
rumors in advance of the OPEC meeting,'' said Bob Baker, an analyst
with Prudential BAche Securities Inc. ``The market is properly not
expecting anything significant to come out of the price committee
meeting. But it's a hopeful sign overall.''
   The five-member pricing committee has no authority to decide
policy but can call a meeting of all 13 members of the cartel. Oil
prices hit two-year lows recently because of the world oversupply
of oil and reports that many OPEC members were exceeding production
quotas.
   The price committee meeting suggests the possibility that OPEC
members might get together and set production limits that would
raise world oil prices.
   The five committee members are Venezuela, Algeria, Saudi Arabia,
Indonesia and Nigeria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
