<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0513EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-IMF-WorldBank Bjt   09-23 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-IMF-World Bank, Bjt,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IMF Chief Pushes Interdependence of Poor and Rich Countries</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top planned about 6 a.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the International Monetary Fund is
urging private bankers to write off some debts owed them by
developing nations, and said the industrial nations need to work
more closely with the Third World to improve the global economy.
   ``There is no prosperity for the industrial countries without
prosperity for the developing countries,'' Michel Camdessus said at
the start of World Bank-International Monetary Fund talks Thursday
in West Berlin.
   Poor countries have been among the best customers of the richer
industrial world. But in recent years, their heavy debt payments
have forced them to cut back their purchases.
   Camdessus praised West Germany, Canada and the Nordic countries
for reducing the debts owed them by the poorest Third World
countries.
   The United States, a major creditor of such countries, has not
forgiven any debts. That would require action by Congress, where
support is weak for foreign aid, especially in an election year.
   Camdessus said private bankers also should write off some debts,
and said he recently has heard more of them discussing the
possibility.
   The World Bank estimates that the Third World debt burden at the
end of 1987 was $1.2 trillion.
   Delegates from the 151 World Bank and IMF member countries as
well as representatives of banking and industry have been arriving
all week for the West Berlin discussions.
   The talks culminate with the Sept. 27-29 joint meeting of the
two sister organizations.
   West Berlin is teeming with police officers hoping to ward off
attempts by leftist militants to disrupt the financial discussions.
   In addition to West Berlin's 6,000-strong force, 2,700 other
police officers have been brought in from across West Germany to
help with security.
   Officials fear violence could erupt in connection with
demonstrations planned by opponents to the policies of the World
Bank and IMF.
   Organizers of the demonstrations contend that Third World
countries are being impoverished by the repayment terms of their
loans.
   Fears of possible violence on West Berlin streets intensified
with Tuesday's failed ambush of a high-ranking West German Finance
Ministry official in Bonn.
   Addressing reporters, Camdessus also spoke about the recent rise
of the U.S. dollar, saying the higher rate would make it harder to
reduce the U.S. international trade deficit.
   A more costly dollar makes imported goods cheaper and more
attractive to Americans, while making American goods more expensive
and thus harder to export.
   But Camdessus also said the increase in the dollar does not
justify too much concern.
   He said that since the 1985 agreement between then-U.S. Treasury
Secretary James A. Baker III and his counterparts from other major
countries, the dollar has continued to fluctuate. But Camdessus
said the fluctuations are less violent and within a narrower range.
   ``This is quite an achievement, it has to be maintained,'' he
said.
   He gets a chance to push his ideas at a meeting Saturday of the
``Group of Seven,'' which brings together the major powers of the
non-Communist world. Nicholas Brady, the new U.S. secretary of the
treasury, will be meeting for the first time with ministers from
Japan, West Germany, Britain, France, Italy and Canada.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880923-0134 </DOCNO>
