<DOCNO> AP880923-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0512EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Drexel-SEC Bjt   09-23 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drexel-SEC, Bjt,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Unlikely For A Year, Evidence Gathering Alone Will Take
Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. lawyers want speedy
access to the Securities and Exchange Commission's evidence to
prepare the Wall Street firm's defense against fraud charges, but a
senior SEC lawyer says that process could take months and trial
probably is a year away.
   Thomas Newkirk, the SEC's chief litigation counsel, made the
remarks Thursday, when the first pretrial hearing on evidence
gathering in the Drexel case took place in Manhattan federal court.
   Newkirk told U.S. District Judge Milton Pollack the enforcement
agency must sort through more than 1 million documents to satisfy
defense requests for information. He also said the sorting process
alone means the SEC cannot even deliver those documents until
mid-December.
   Asked later by reporters for his opinion on when the trial
finally could proceed, Newkirk said: ``It will take at least a year
to get ready for trial.''
   The hearing produced no decisions. However, it marked the first
confrontation between Drexel and SEC lawyers in open court since
the agency announced its unprecedented enforcement action Sept. 7
against the investment firm and some key employees, notably
high-yield bond financier Michael Milken.
   The defendants were accused of scheming with now-imprisoned
speculator Ivan Boesky to trade on inside information, manipulate
stock, bully Drexel clients and engage in other securities frauds.
   If they lose, Drexel and the other defendants could face
penalties in the hundreds of millions of dollars and possible
expulsion from the securities business. The firm has denied
wrongdoing.
   The SEC action stemmed directly from revelations by Boesky, who
is cooperating with federal investigators and is expected to be
their star witness in the case.
   The Drexel defense team, comprised of some the most astute and
expensive attorneys in the country, told Pollack it could not even
estimate a trial date until the SEC had supplied at least some of
the documents requested.
   Defense lawyers Arthur Liman and Thomas Curnin also questioned
Pollack's proposal to merge the evidence-gathering processes in the
Drexel case with those in civil suits he is hearing against Boesky.
Liman said that could cause complications and delays.
   ``All we want is our own case,'' Liman said. ``The SEC brought a
case against our clients. We'd like our case to be a separate case
with the SEC.''
   Pollack assured the defense team he was interested in
efficiently completing the evidence-gathering phase and moving to
trial.
   Quickly settling the pretrial fact-gathering issue is crucial to
Drexel's defense strategy because a federal grand jury is
investigating the firm and may deliver an indictment soon, lawyers
familiar with the case have said.
   If that happens, the criminal charges would take precedence over
the SEC's civil charges and severely limit Drexel's ability to seek
evidence, because of stricter federal rules in criminal cases.
   Pollack did not rule on any evidence-gathering guidelines and
set another hearing for Oct. 11.
   At that time, the Drexel defense is expected to ask Pollack to
disqualify himself from the case on grounds it is basically
unrelated to the civil suits against Boesky.
   The SEC had requested that Pollack take the case, bypassing the
normal procedure of random judge selection, on grounds that he is
intimately familiar with the Boesky litigation.
   Pollack, an octogenarian jurist known for his toughness and
pro-government leanings, is expected to reject any defense move to
seek another judge.
   Asked whether the SEC is happy that Pollack appears determined
to remain in charge, Newkirk told reporters, ``we're happy with any
unbiased judge.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880923-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0512EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Delta-Jets Bjt   09-23 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delta-Jets, Bjt,0739</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delta Places Orders, Options For 215 Aircraft</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In what may be an industry record, Delta Air
Lines has announced orders and options for 215 jets from two
companies in a deal analysts said would be worth at least $6
billion.
   Atlanta-based Delta said it ordered nine MD-11s from McDonnell
Douglas Corp. and nine 767-300ERs from Boeing Co. It also ordered
Pratt & Whitney PW4000-series engines to power the planes, in a
deal worth $1.75 billion.
   The company did not put a value on the options for the remaining
197 aircraft, but analysts said the total would be more than $6
billion. Some put the deal at more than $10 billion, well above the
record $5.04 billion purchase of 100 Boeing and 30 Airbus Industrie
jets last May by International Lease Finance Corp., of Beverly
Hills, Calif.
   ``These new orders and options...highlight our international and
domestic growth plans and commitment to maintaining the most modern
fleet of aircraft available,'' Ron Allen, Delta chairman and chief
executive officer, said in a statement.
   Delta, the nation's third largest airline, also announced
options on 31 more MD-11s, 16 more 767-300ERs, 100 MD-88s and 50
Boeing 757-232s.
   Delta had been known to be contemplating a large order for
months. It did not provide a total cost of the package.
   Spokesman Jim Lundy said Delta chose the MD-11 because of the
nature of the airline's routes in the Pacific, where most of the
planes will be used.
   The twin-engine 767-300ERs _ for ``extended range'' _ will be
used on transatlantic flights, and will carry about 220 passengers.
The MD-11 is a three-engine plane that, in Delta's configuration,
will carry 276 passengers.
   Analyst Robert Decker with Duff & Phelps in Chicago said the
MD-11 order was the first by a domestic airline, but only would
affect other airlines' decision if it caused McDonnell Douglas to
lower the price of the jet.
   Delta operates a fleet of 383 airplanes, and the purchases
announced Thursday will be used for expansion and replacement,
according to spokesman Jim Lundy.
   But the MD-11s generally were intended to expand the airline's
fleet, Lundy said.
   ``Delta's always been one that kept a modern fleet and (the
order) says they're going to maintain their position and that they
intend to keep pace with the growth...in the consolidated
industry,'' said Lee Howard, executive vice president of Airline
Economics Inc., a consulting firm in Washington, D.C.
   The order was the second large purchase for Delta since January
1986, when the Atlanta-based company ordered 80 MD-88s from
McDonnell Douglas and 185 engines from Pratt & Whitney in a deal
worth $2.5 billion.
   Delta said Thursday it still has options remaining on 42
757-200s, 12 767-300s and 85 MD-88s.
   Lundy said the airline had not decided how the new purchases
would be financed, but said the company has a $1 billion line of
bank credit and was in an excellent financial position.
   Delta, which has about 48,000 employees, earned $306.83 million
on $6.92 billion in revenue during the fiscal year ended June 30.
   Boeing Commercial Airplanes spokesman Tom Cole said the nine
767s would be worth roughly $745 million, including spare parts and
training.
   Howard said the order was just the latest in what already was a
record plane-buying year.
   Boeing now has received orders for 316 767s, including 48 this
year. The company earlier this year set an aircraft-industry record
for planes ordered in one year, and the Delta order boosts that to
485 planes worth about $22 billion, Cole said.
   At a price of about $44 million apiece, the 50 757s would be
worth about $2.2 billion, if all orders are exercised, Cole said.
The 16 767-300ERs would be worth approximately $1.15 billion. Spare
parts and training could increase those figures.
   McDonnell Douglas spokesman Don Hanson said his company does not
release price information about its planes. Industry experts
estimate an MD-11, a successor to the DC-10, costs about $100
million, and a 142-passenger MD-88 costs about $25 million. At
those prices, the 40 MD-11s would be worth $4 billion, and the 100
MD-88s $2.5 billion.
   The first 767s will be delivered to Delta in early 1990, with
the initial MD-11s delivered to Delta in the spring of 1991.
</TEXT>
