<DOCNO> AP880923-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0625EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SEC-WPPSS     09-23 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SEC-WPPSS,0796</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dingell Says He's Less Than Satisfied With SEC Decision On WPPSS
Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Energy and Commerce
Committee says he's not happy with the Securities and Exchange
Commission's decision not to pursue enforcement action in the
largest municipal bond default in history.
   Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., said the SEC's decision in the $2.25
billion bond default by the Washington Public Power Supply System
``is not well received by WPPSS bondholders or by me.
   ``Investors in municipal securities have the same right to
accurate and full disclosure as any other investors and liability
should fall firmly on those who defraud them,'' Dingell said.
   Dingell said the SEC's plans to terminate the WPPSS
investigation ``will be looked at and addressed vigorously by the
committee at the earliest possible time.''
   In a massive report released Thursday, the commission's staff
laid out a ``factual'' account of the supply system's problems in
trying to build two nuclear power plants in Washington state but
drew no legal conclusions.
   The report found, in general, that WPPSS tried to put the best
image possible on the deepening construction and financial problems
that led up to the default in 1983 and in some cases ``avoided
disclosure of negative developments.''
   Others, including the bond underwriters, bond counsel and the
rating agencies, were not agressive enough in asking questions and
exercising ``due diligence'' to ensure that investors were aware of
the supply system's mounting problems, the report stated.
   SEC Chairman David Ruder said that while he was ``very concerned
about the failure of the system'' in the sale of the WPPSS bonds, a
prolonged enforcement action would be a drain on the commission's
resources.
   Ruder also said it would be difficult to determine who was
responsible for ``deficiencies'' in the bond's disclosure reports,
and that bondholders already were trying to recover their
investments through a civil trial currently underway in Tucson.
   The commission did decide to offer for public comment a proposed
rule that would impose stricter disclosure requirements on issuers
of municipal bonds and the securities firms that sell them.
   Oregon Democratic Rep. Ron Wyden, a member of the House Energy
Committee, said he was concerned the SEC is indicating it doesn't
have the money and staff to pursue such massive cases.
   ``It sends a message that if you mess up, mess up big because
the principal regulatory agency doesn't have the resources to
pursue enforcement action,'' said Wyden.
   The SEC report concluded the default resulted from extensive
cost overruns and construction delays at WPPSS Projects No. 4 and
No. 5 in Washington state.
   Cost of the projects had soared from an initial estimate of
slightly over $2 billion to almost $12 billion before construction
was halted in 1981.
   Both projects were abandoned in January 1982 and in 1983 WPPSS
quit making payments on the bonds after the Washington state
Supreme Court held that the utilities' contracts with the
consortium were illegal and thus unenforceable. Without payments
from the 88 participating utilities, many in other states, WPPSS
defaulted.
   As early as 1978, the report said, WPPSS recognized it could
face long-term financing problems. Top supply system officials told
the 88 utilities participating in the projects in late 1980 that
WPPSS' ``cash flow coverage was so low that there was almost none
at times,'' the report said.
   The report said the participants, also in late 1980, asked the
supply system to study the possibility of slowing down construction
or terminating the two projects.
   The request was kept confidential because of its possible impact
on the financial markets and WPPSS contiuned to sell bonds, more
than $400 million worth, before the projects were scrubbed, the
report said.
   The report found that WPPSS also failed to adequately disclose
in the official bond statements that forecasts showed a drop in the
demand for electricity in the Northwest.
   As for others involved in the WPPSS bond sales, the report said:
   _Underwriters were aware of the supply system's problems but did
not conduct ``due diligence-type'' investigations to verify WPPSS's
disclosure reports as they do with other securities sales.
   The underwriters contend they had no legal obligation to conduct
an investigation and it was not industry practice to do so in
competitive municipal bond sales.
   _WPPSS's bond counsel and special counsel, despite ``indications
of legal difficulties'' with provisions requiring the utilities to
pay for the plants whether they were finished or not gave the bonds
a clean bill of health.
   _Rating agencies depended too much on information supplied by
WPPSS and did too little study of their own in rating the bonds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
