<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0902EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MinimumWage     09-23 0748</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Minimum Wage,0771</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republicans Pressing Filibuster To Force Democrat Concession</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Vote scheduled to begin at 11 a.m. EDT; pre-noon top
expected. A version moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans stalling action on a bill to raise
the $3.35 minimum wage are vowing to continue their filibuster
until Democrats accede to an 80 percent subminimum for any newly
hired employee.
   A vote on a second Democratic attempt to break the filibuster
was scheduled today. While GOP leaders conceded that some support
for their delay tactics may be wavering, others vowed to continue
the parliamentary fight, if necessary, until Congress adjourns in
mid-October.
   On a 53-43 vote _ six short of the 60 needed _ the Senate
refused Thursday to limit to 30 hours further debate on the bill by
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., to raise the wage floor to $3.75
an hour in January, $4.15 in 1990 and $4.55 in 1991.
   ``I hope that our friends on the other side of the aisle will
have a change of heart overnight,'' Senate Majority Leader Robert
C. Byrd, D-W.Va., said after the vote. ``It's only clear that there
is a deliberate attempt to stall action on this bill.''
   The stalemate has existed since Sept. 17 when Sen. Orrin Hatch,
R-Utah, filed an amendment that would establish a 90-day subminimum
rate at the current floor of $3.35 an hour for new hires. The
subminium would be raised to $3.65 an hour in 1991.
   President Reagan, Vice President George Bush and Bush's running
mate, Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind., all have demanded that any increase
in the minimum wage be coupled with the creation of a subminimum.
   While Bush, Quayle and Hatch have referred to the proposal as a
``training'' wage or a ``youth training'' wage, Hatch's amendment
does not have the word ``training'' in it, nor any age limitations
on its application.
   Immediately after Hatch's amendment was introduced, Kennedy
filed a substitute for it that would slightly expand a currently
allowed but little-used 85 percent subminimum wage for full-time
students working less than 20 hours a week.
   Because Hatch's subminimum proposal would die under the Senate's
rules if Kennedy's is approved, Republicans have refused to allow
votes on it or any other amendments.
   ``They don't want to vote on the Kennedy amendment because it
will prevail and they don't like that,'' Kennedy said. He said it
would represent ``a vote against the plan that Bush hatched.''
   Bush in the past two weeks has said he supports an increase in
the minimum wage _ never specifying how much _ but only if it is
accompanied by a subminimum floor.
   Quayle has repeatedly advocated an increase to $4 an hour over
two years coupled with a subminimum.
   ``We're not going to get a fair hearing on the training wage
because the labor leaders don't want it,'' complained Senate
Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas. ``It's not the Republicans
vs. the Demorats; it's the Republicans vs. the labor leaders.
They're telling us we can take this or leave; we're not going to
play that game.''
   AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland said Republicans ``obviously
know that the presidential nominee of their party, George Bush,
wasn't serious when he told Americans he wanted an increase in the
minimum wage.''
   Sen. Alan Dixon, D-Ill., said Bush could break the logjam with
``seven phone calls'' to Republican senators supporting the
filibuster.
   Kennedy predicted the bill's supporters would pick up additional
support on today's cloture vote but maybe not enough to break the
logjam.
   ``It's an open secret that the White House has asked the
Republicans to keep voting for a filibuster tomorrow and next
week,'' he said.
   Dole conceded that some members of his party might bolt today,
saying, ``We might not be successful, but we're going to try.''
   Other Republicans, however, vowed to continue the fight, if
necessary, until Congress adjourns.
   ``We could very well be on this bill for the remaining month,''
said Sen. Steve Symms, R-Idaho. ``We don't have the votes to repeal
the minimum wage, which is what we should be doing at a time of
economic expansion.''
   On Thursday's vote, three Republicans _ Sens. Lowell Weicker of
Connecticut, William Roth of Delaware and John Chafee of Rhode
Island _ joined 50 Democrats to end the filibuster.
   Three Democrats _ Sens. James Exon of Nebraska, David Boren of
Oklahoma and Richard Shelby of Alabama _ joined Republicans in
voting then to allow it to continue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
