<1ST_LINE>u f PM-IMF-WorldBanks 1stLd-Writethru f0010 09-23 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-IMF-World Banks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0010,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West German Minister Rejects Call For Debt Forgiveness</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with West German finance minister
rejecting call for debt forgiveness. No pickup. A version moving on
general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The West German finance minister today rejected
even partial debt forgiveness for heavily indebted, middle-income
countries, despite the urging of the head of the International
Monetary Fund.
   But the minister, Gerhard Stoltenberg, also said he expected
that other major nations would join West Germany in reducing
interest rates on the massive debts owed by some poorer countries.
   ``There is no cause to discuss debt forgiveness'' for the
middle-income countries, Stoltenberg told reporters on the second
day of discussions leading up to the formal annual joint meetings
of the World Bank and International Monetary Fund next week.
   Countries whose people have average incomes above $750 a year
are considered middle-income countries. Brazil is the most heavily
indebted of these, owing $121 billion, followed by Mexico and
Argentina. The World Bank says the Third World debt burden at the
end of 1987 was $1.2 trillion.
   On Thursday, Michael Camdessus, chief of the International
Monetary Fund, urged industrial nations to write off some debts of
developing countries for the good of both groups. ``There is no
prosperity for the industrial countries without prosperity for the
developing countries,'' Camdessus told reporters.
   Camdessus spoke at the opening of international banking talks as
thousands of police patrolled West Berlin to prevent violence
during demonstrations planned by bank critics. They charge that
Third World countries are crushed under the weight of their debt to
wealthier nations.
   Fears of violence grew Tuesday when two masked men armed with at
least one shotgun fired at Hans Tietmeyer. The shots missed the
official of the West German Finance Ministry who helped plan the
international banking talks.
   Stoltenberg also said he opposes any suggestions for a worldwide
debt forgiveness. ``Calls for a global solution destroy the
creditworthiness of debtor countries,'' Stoltenberg said.
   He said debt problems should be solved on a case-by-case basis
and West Germany would rather restructure debt and improve
conditions than forgive loans. The West German government this week
announced additional concessions to the poorest countries. ``We
have verbal indications that the British and French governments
will make similar decisions,'' he said.
   Stoltenberg also said major industrial nations such as the
United States should strive for a closer alignment of their
economic policies, and that he wants to avoid ``strong swings in
foreign exchange rates.''
   The West German finance minister said he met Thursday with the
new U.S. treasury secretary, Nicholas Brady. He declined to go into
details on the talks, but said he expected U.S. economic policies
to remain unchanged.
   Stoltenberg is scheduled to meet with Brady and the top finance
officials from the five other major Western industrialized nations
on Saturday.
   Finance ministers from 24 developing countries are slated to
meet as well on Saturday and are expected to seek more aid from
governments as well as from commercial banks. They are also seeking
a cancellation of some debts.
   Delegates from the 151 World Bank and IMF member countries as
well as representatives of banking and industry have been arriving
all week for the West Berlin discussions.
   The talks culminate with the Sept. 27-29 joint meeting of the
two sister organizations, which lend money to governments for
development projects.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
