<DOCNO> AP880923-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0048EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-NewChryslers     09-23 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Chryslers,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler Introduces '89s, Hoping To Hold Own in Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. introduced its 1989
cars and trucks Thursday, and a top executive said the company has
a tough task in holding its share of the market.
   ``We're going to struggle to hold car share,'' said Gerald
Greenwald, chairman of the company's Chrysler Motors car-making
arm. ``We are going through a transition year of dropping some of
the old'' models.
   He said the truck market should not be a problem. ``We don't see
any strong competition on our minivan,'' he said.
   Chrysler opened the minivan market in the early 1980s with its
Dodge Caravan and Plymouth Voyager, both front-wheel drive
vehicles. Since then, other domestic and foreign makers have jumped
into the rapidly expanding market, but Chrysler's two models have
held the market lead.
   ``We see us holding our own, maybe a little plus,'' Greenwald
said.
   During the past several years, the No. 3 U.S. automaker has lost
market share in cars while gaining in light trucks.
   During the same period, it has dealt with the acquisition of
American Motors Corp. While AMC brought employees that sometimes
performed redundant work of their Chrysler counterparts, the
acquisition brought hot-selling Jeep vehicles to the Chrysler
lineup.
   ``God bless minivans and Jeeps,'' said Ben Bidwell, president
for products and marketing for Chrysler Motors. ``We're going to
have to stretch to equal the '88 volume and (market) share.''
   At the end of last month, Chrysler held 14.3 percent of the
U.S.-made car market and 22.7 percent of the domestically made
light truck market.
   The major changes for 1989 include a new four-speed automatic
transmission, called Ultradrive; a 2.5-liter, four-cylinder engine;
and antilock braking systems on more vehicles, including all four
wheels on the Jeep Cherokee.
   Company executives also repeated that more Chrysler cars have
air bags as standard equipment than any other automaker and that by
the 1990 model year, air bags will be standard on U.S.-built cars.
   Later in the '89 model year, Chrysler will introduce the
mid-size '89 Acclaim and the 1990 Laser, designed to compete with
the Ford Probe and other cars.
</TEXT>
