<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Obit-Coleman     09-23 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Obit-Coleman,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Son Of Coleman Co. Founder Dies At 86</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sheldon Coleman, chairman of the board of
the Coleman Co. and son of its founder, has died at the age of 86.
   Coleman, who died Wednesday night, joined his father's company
in 1925 shortly after being graduated from Cornell University with
a mechanical engineering degree. He became Coleman Co. chief
executive officer and executive vice president in October, 1940 and
its chairman in 1957.
   His son, Sheldon C. Coleman, is the company's president.
   The publicly held company that had record sales of nearly $600
million and more than 5,000 employees in 1987 was founded by W.C.
Coleman in 1900 in Kingfisher, Okla. as a lighting-service
business, leasing lamps and servicing them.
   In 1901, the business moved to Wichita, where it began producing
lamps in 1905. It developed its Coleman lanterns, which lengthened
the farmer's day, in 1914.
   In 1920s, the company prospered. But the Coleman family almost
lost the company during the Great Depression.
   Coleman saw rural electrification coming and recommended the
company diversify by developing oil space heaters and gas floor
furnaces in the 1930s.
   During the 1960s Coleman led another diversification effort,
expanding the company's lantern and camp stove production into
dozens of outdoor recreation products. The company eventually
became the world's largest manufacturer of such items.
   A funeral is scheduled for 3 p.m. Saturday at Wichita's
Metropolitan Baptist Church. A Memorial has been established with
the Coleman Chairtable Trust.
   Besides his son, Coleman's survivors include his wife, Galey; a
brother, Clarence; two daughters, two stepsons, a stepdaughter, 14
grandchildren and five great-grandchildren.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880923-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0115EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Ecuador-Oil     09-23 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ecuador-Oil,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Ecuadoran Government Says It Wants Foreign Investment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new center-left government said
Thursday it welcomes foreign investment and was concerned its
recent decision to assume operating control of much of the nation's
oil industry would be misinterpreted as a nationalization.
   Energy Minister Diego Tamariz met with foreign correspondents to
stress that the decision to assume operating control of various
stages of production and refining over the next several years did
not mean the government has ``the intention of taking action
against the assets of foreign companies through nationalizing
them.''
   The government said earlier this week that the state oil company
CEPE would assume control next year of the pipeline, which brings
oil from the eastern jungle, when the pipeline service contract
with U.S. oil company Texaco Inc. ends in 1989.
   It said CEPE would take control of production wells now operated
by Texaco when production contracts end in 1990 and also would buy
two refineries owned by private investors.
   ``We are worried that this may create an image abroad that we do
not want foreign investment in the country when in fact we are open
to foreign investment in terms of mutual benefit,'' Tamariz said.
   The government has said it would respect oil exploration
contracts that the previous government of conservative President
Leon Febres Cordero signed with 13 foreign companies.
   ``The principal concern is that the image we have given is not
real. That is to say, the image of a government nationalizing when
we are taking control of operations that correspond to the state
company under contract terms,'' Tamariz said.
   Texaco produces nearly 80 percent of Ecuador's daily output of
310,000 barrels.
   President Rodrigo Borja, a moderate leftist, took office Aug. 10
pledging to impose controls on the free-market economic system
favored by Febres Cordero. He had indicated during his campaign
that he also would be more selective than his predecessor about
foreign investment in Ecuador.
</TEXT>
