<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BenefitPlanIndictments 2ndLd-Writethru f0296 09-23 0789</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Benefit Plan Indictments, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0296,0803</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>10 Accused of Defrauding Employee Benefit Plans</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd graf pvs, bgng: ``Angelo Commito
...'' to UPDATE with arrest; INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf pvs,
bgng: ``In an ...'' to UPDATE with United comment; INSERTS 1 graf
after 12th graf pvs, bgng: ``Commito and ..'' to UPDATE with
Commito released on bond.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A San Francisco health care executive and nine
other people were charged with defrauding employee benefit plans in
Atlanta, Chicago and the state of California, the Justice
Department said Thursday.
   Angelo Commito, a health care service provider and consultant to
employee benefit plans, was charged in Atlanta in a scheme to
defraud the Munford Corp., a retailer, in connection with the award
of a pre-paid optical benefit program for the company's employees.
   Commito, of Palm Desert, Calif., was arrested Thursday by FBI
agents as he arrived at the Palm Springs, Calif., Municipal
Airport, said spokesman Jim Neilson of the FBI's Los Angeles office.
   In an indictment unsealed in Baltimore, Commito, United
HealthCare Inc. and United's vice president for marketing, Alan
Cohn of Owings Mills, Md., were accused of devising a scheme to pay
a government agent who posed as Munford's agent for selecting the
optical program.
   United's president and chief operating officer, Bill Slavin,
said his company was ``innocent of all charges.'' United provides
prepaid optical, dental and medical prescription services to more
than a million families in 42 states.
   Two indictments unsealed in Atlanta accused Commito and five
other people of conspiracy, mail fraud, wire fraud and money
laundering in a plan to defraud Munford and its employee welfare
plan in the selection of a second pre-paid optical program and an
alcohol and drug abuse counseling program. The plan allegedly
involved using Commito's companies to pay a government agent who
posed as Munford's representative for the purchase of the programs.
   One of two indictments issued in Chicago accused Commito and
Carl Mattison, 64, of Aptos, Calif., of conspiracy, paying
kickbacks to an employee pension plan official and embezzlement of
pension fund money in changing life insurance carriers for
employees in a pension fund.
   The fund was for members of Service Employees International
Union 1. William Wire, 52, former manager of the fund, was charged
with conspiracy, receipt of kickbacks, embezzlement and concealing
the kickbacks, resulting in the filing of a false report with the
U.S. Labor Department.
   Also charged in Chicago was William Hainsworth, 45, of Winfield,
Ill., former administrator of the Welfare Fund sponsored by the
DuPage County, Ill., Cement Masons Union. Hainsworth was accused of
embezzling welfare fund money, falsifying fund records and making
false statements to a grand jury.
   The grand jury investigated a plan in which Hainsworth allegedly
concealed his execution of dental and optical care contracts that
weren't disclosed to fund trustees and participating employees. One
of the contracts involved a company operated by Commito, Labor and
Health Benefit Plans Inc.
   In San Diego, Commito and three other people were accused of
defrauding Eye Care U.S.A. of money used to establish two optical
care companies in which Commito and one of the other defendants,
Elliott Kusel, held financial interests.
   In San Francisco, Commito and Mattison were accused of
conspiring to violate the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt
Organization statute and embezzlement and kickbacks in connection
with employee benefits plan funds.
   Commito and Mattison were charged with embezzlement and
unlawfully receiving kickbacks in connection with the selection of
an alcohol and drug abuse rehabilitation program for people
participating in the Western Employers Trust, a welfare benefit
plan for employees in central and northern California. The two were
accused of stealing benefit plan money that was added to the cost
of the program in order to generate unlawful fees.
   Commito and Mattison also were accused of devising a scheme to
defraud the National Semiconductor Corp. of Santa Clara, Calif., of
money the two allegedly agreed would be used to pay kickbacks to a
government undercover agent who posed as the company
representative. The kickbacks were to persuade the firm to buy an
alcohol and drug rehabilitation program.
   Commito appeared before U.S. Magistrate George L. Marin in Yucca
Valley, Calif., where bail was set at $1 million. Commito posted a
$100,000 deposit and was released, the FBI's Neilson said.
   Also charged in the Atlanta indictments were Mattison; Monica
Oss, 32, of Washington, D.C.; Elliott Kusel, 54, of San Diego; Marc
Lee Kusel, 30, of Mission Viejo, Calif.; and Thomas Parnham, 39, of
Reston, Va.
   Also charged in the San Diego indictment were the two Kusels and
Cheryl Fyten, former vice president of personnel at Eye Care
U.S.A., a San Diego optical service provider.
</TEXT>
