<DOCNO> AP880923-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-88 0443EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-WPPSSTrial     09-23 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WPPSS Trial,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Testimony Begins In Mammoth WPPSS Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of several utilities helped
guide a failed attempt to build two nuclear power plants that led
to a historic bond default by the Washington Public Power Supply
System, according to the opening witness at Thursday's fraud trial
stemming from the default.
   The utility representatives served on boards and committees that
decided there was a need for more power, approved the projects and
drew up the agreements under which 88 public utilities would
participate in building the plants and sharing the power, said
WPPSS employee Harlan R. Kosmata.
   WPPSS defaulted on $2.25 billion in municipal bonds, the largest
such default in U.S. history, when the Washington Supreme Court
ruled in 1983 that the public utilities had no authority to sign
those participation agreements.
   A class of 24,000 bondholders and Chemical Bank of New York, a
trustee for bondholders, are suing 15 utilities, two engineering
firms and a financial company for fraud.
   Attorneys for the bondholders have maintained the defendants
conspired to lie and withhold information in order to sell the
bonds. Had that information been revealed, they contend, the bonds
never would have been sold.
   They have also maintained the utilities wielded power over WPPSS
to build the plants.
   Kosmata, under questioning by Chemical Bank attorney Thomas
Barr, noted many of the same employees of the utilities either were
elected or appointed to several panels that had decision power over
the projects.
   Kosmata was liaison between WPPSS and the utilities in the
projects. He also was secretary for the participants committee, a
group of seven people that made decisions for all the utilities in
the projects.
   Representatives for several large utilities, including
defendants Tacoma and Snohomish County, sat on the participants
committee and also were members of the WPPSS board of directors,
the WPPSS executive committee and the Public Power Council, an
organization of public utilities in the Northwest, Kosmata said.
   All of them were involved in deciding when, how and where the
plants would be built and how the financing would occur, he
testified.
   Kosmata said the WPPSS board of directors consisted of people
representing and chosen by utility members.
   The board ``acted on significant issues'' concerning the plants,
he said. ``In layman's terms, it did have control of the supply
system.''
   Kosmata testified for the plaintiffs and was expected to resume
his testimony Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
